sup> <small> Includes [[Coupe de France]], [[Coupe de la Ligue]], [[Scottish Cup]], [[Scottish League Cup]], [[FA Cup]] and [[EFL Cup|Football League Cup]]</small> </div>\n\n===Managerial record===\n{{updated|match played 7th March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team\n!rowspan=2|From\n!rowspan=2|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n!rowspan=2|{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!{{abbr|P|Matches played}}!!{{abbr|W|Matches won}}!!{{abbr|D|Matches drawn}}!!{{abbr|L|Matches lost}}!!{{abbr|Win %|Win percentage}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n|align=left|20 December 2019\n|align=left|''Present''\n{{WDL|16|8|6|2}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sofascore.com/manager/mikel-arteta/794075 |title=Mikel Arteta managerial statistics |website=SofaScore |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n{{WDLtot|16|8|6|2}}\n!\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Paris Saint-Germain'''\n*[[UEFA Intertoto Cup]]: [[2001 UEFA Intertoto Cup|2001]]<ref>{{cite news \n|url=https://www.repubblica.it/online/sport/intertoto/uefa/uefa.html\n|title= Brescia, sogno finito il Psg va in Uefa\n|publisher=Repubblica.it\n|accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Rangers'''\n*[[Scottish Premier League]]: [[2002\u201303 Scottish Premier League|2002\u201303]]<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Glenda |editor1-last=Rollin |editor2-first=Jack |editor2-last=Rollin |title=Sky Sports Football Yearbook 2003\u20132004 |year=2003 |publisher=Headline Publishing Group |location=London |isbn=978-0-7553-1228-3 |pages=698\u2013699, 712}}</ref>\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: [[2002\u201303 Scottish League Cup|2002\u201303]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/2853133.stm |title=Rangers retain CIS Cup |website=BBC Sport |date=16 March 2003 |accessdate=3 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Arsenal'''\n*[[FA Cup]]: [[2013\u201314 FA Cup|2013\u201314]],<ref name=2014FACupFinal/> [[2014\u201315 FA Cup|2014\u201315]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32856754 |title=Arsenal 4\u20130 Aston Villa |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=30 May 2015 |accessdate=3 December 2019}}<br />{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/fa-cup-final-arsenal-thrash-villa-828gx85h3v3 |title=FA Cup final: Arsenal thrash Villa |first=Howard |last=Swains |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=30 May 2015 |accessdate=3 December 2019 |url-access=registration |quote=Mikel Arteta, the Arsenal club captain, leads the team up the famous stairs and is first to collect his winner's medal from Prince William.}}</ref>\n*[[FA Community Shield]]: [[2014 FA Community Shield|2014]],<ref name=2014CommunityShield/> [[2015 FA Community Shield|2015]]<ref name=2015CommunityShield/>\n\n'''Spain U16'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-16 Championship]]: [[1999 UEFA European Under-16 Championship|1999]]<ref name=RSSSF>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/ec-u16-99.html |title=European U16 Football Championship 1999 |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation}}</ref>\n\n'''Spain U18'''\n*[[UEFA\u2013CAF Meridian Cup]]: [[1999 UEFA\u2013CAF Meridian Cup|1999]]{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[List of Scottish Premier League monthly award winners|Scottish Premier League Young Player of the Month]]: September 2002, August 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.myfootballfacts.com/world-football/scottish-football/spl_manager_and_player_of_the_month_awards/|title=Scottish Premier League / Scottish Professional Football League Manager and Player of the Month Award 2000\u201301 to 2018\u201319\n|website=My Football Facts|accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n*[[List of Everton F.C. records and statistics#Evertonfc.com player awards|Everton Player of the Season]]: [[2005\u201306 Everton F.C. season|2005\u201306]], [[2006\u201307 Everton F.C. season|2006\u201307]]<ref name=EFC />\n*[[List of Everton F.C. records and statistics#Evertonfc.com player awards|Everton Players' Player of the Season]]: 2005\u201306<ref name=EFC />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111129122147/http://www.arsenal.com/first-team/players/mikel-arteta Arsenal F.C. Profile]\n*{{BDFutbol}}\n*[http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/player.php?playerid=1219 Rangers profile at ''fitbastats.com'']\n*{{Soccerway}}\n*{{LFP}}\n\n{{Arsenal F.C. squad}}\n{{Premier League managers}}\n{{Everton F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{Arsenal F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arteta, Mikel}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Sebasti\u00e1n]]\n[[Category:Basque footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Antiguoko players]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona C players]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona B players]]\n[[Category:Paris Saint-Germain F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Real Sociedad footballers]]\n[[Category:Everton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Arsenal F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Spain youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Arsenal F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Pro Licence holders]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in England]]\n[[Category:Premier League managers]]\n", "name_user": "Uttermehhness", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added missing citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mikel_Arteta"}
{"title_page": "Sons of Bitches", "text_new": "{{short description|1990 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sons of Bitches\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Leonid Filatov]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = Leonid Filatov\n| starring       = [[Vladimir Ilyin (actor)|Vladimir Ilyin]]<br>[[Larisa Udovichenko]]<br>[[Aleksandr Abdulov]]<br>[[Evgeni Evstigneev]]<br>[[Liya Akhedzhakova]], Vladimir Samoilov\n| music          = Vladimir Komarov\n| cinematography = [[Pavel Lebeshev]]\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1990}}\n| runtime        = 98 minutes\n| country        = Soviet Union\n| language       = Russian\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Sons of Bitches''''' ({{lang-ru|link=no|\u0421\u0443\u043a\u0438\u043d\u044b \u0434\u0435\u0442\u0438}}, [[Transliteration|translit.]]&nbsp;Sukiny deti) is a 1990 Soviet [[drama film]] directed by [[Leonid Filatov]]. It was entered into the [[17th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Moscow1991\">{{cite web |url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff38/eng/archives/?year=1991 |title=17th Moscow International Film Festival (1991) |accessdate=9 October 2016 |work=MIFF}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe plot of the film is based on real historical events in [[Taganka Theater]], when its leader [[Yuri Lyubimov]] left the [[USSR]] (1984), and made a number of anti-Party statements, after which he was removed from the management of the theater and deprived of citizenship.  ''Sons of bitches''  tells how the troupe has apprehended these events and the pressure the state put on them, and also shows events that have not happened \u2013 the actors' strike, the hunger strike, the threat of self-immolation. A functionary is sent to the theater from the Ministry \u2013 Yuri Mikhailovich, who is to restore order in the rebellious cultural institution. The story ends in tragedy \u2013 with the death of one of the protesters.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Vladimir Ilyin (actor)|Vladimir Ilyin]] as Leva Busygin\n* [[Larisa Udovichenko]] as Tatyana, Busygin's wife\n* [[Aleksandr Abdulov]] as Igor Gordynsky\n* [[Evgeni Evstigneev]] as Andrey Ivanovich Nanaytsev\n* [[Liya Akhedzhakova]] as Ella Ernestovna, Nanaytsev's wife\n* [[Vladimir Yakovlevich Samoilov|Vladimir Samoilov]] as Pyotr Yegorovich, Theater's Director\n* [[Yelena Tsyplakova]] as Lidiya Nikolaevna Fedyaeva\n* [[Tatyana Kravchenko]] as Serafima Mikhailovna Korzukhina\n* [[Nina Shatskaya (actress)|Nina Shatskaya]] as Elena Konstantinovna Gvozdilova\n* [[Sergey Makovetskiy]] as Borya Sinyukhaev\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0100714|Sons of Bitches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sons Of Bitches}}\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:1990s drama films]]\n[[Category:Soviet films]]\n[[Category:Soviet drama films]]\n[[Category:Russian-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:1990 directorial debut films]]\n\n\n{{1990s-USSR-film-stub}}\n{{1990s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1990 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sons of Bitches\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Leonid Filatov]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = Leonid Filatov\n| starring       = [[Vladimir Ilyin (actor)|Vladimir Ilyin]]<br>[[Larisa Udovichenko]]<br>[[Aleksandr Abdulov]]<br>[[Evgeni Evstigneev]]<br>[[Liya Akhedzhakova]], Vladimir Samoilov\n| music          = Vladimir Komarov\n| cinematography = [[Pavel Lebeshev]]\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1990}}\n| runtime        = 98 minutes\n| country        = Soviet Union\n| language       = Russian\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Sons of Bitches''''' ({{lang-ru|link=no|\u0421\u0443\u043a\u0438\u043d\u044b \u0434\u0435\u0442\u0438}}, [[Transliteration|translit.]]&nbsp;Sukiny deti) is a 1990 Soviet [[drama film]] directed by [[Leonid Filatov]]. It was entered into the [[17th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Moscow1991\">{{cite web |url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff38/eng/archives/?year=1991 |title=17th Moscow International Film Festival (1991) |accessdate=9 October 2016 |work=MIFF}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe plot of the film is based on real historical events in [[Taganka Theater]], when its leader [[Yuri Lyubimov]] left the [[USSR]] (1984), and made a number of anti-Party statements, after which he was removed from the management of the theater and deprived of citizenship.  ''Sons of bitches''  tells how the troupe has apprehended these events and the pressure the state put on them, and also shows events that have not happened \u2013 the actors' strike, the hunger strike, the threat of self-immolation. A functionary is sent to the theater from the Ministry \u2013 Yuri Mikhailovich, who is to restore order in the rebellious cultural institution. The story ends in tragedy \u2013 with the death of one of the protesters.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Vladimir Ilyin (actor)|Vladimir Ilyin]] as Leva Busygin\n* [[Larisa Udovichenko]] as Tatyana, Busygin's wife\n* [[Aleksandr Abdulov]] as Igor Gordynsky\n* [[Evgeni Evstigneev]] as Andrey Ivanovich Nanaytsev\n* [[Liya Akhedzhakova]] as Ella Ernestovna, Nanaytsev's wife\n* [[Vladimir Yakovlevich Samoilov|Vladimir Samoilov]] as Pyotr Yegorovich, Theater's Director\n* [[Yelena Tsyplakova]] as Lidiya Nikolaevna Fedyaeva\n* [[Tatyana Kravchenko]] as Serafima Mikhailovna Korzukhina\n* [[Nina Shatskaya (actress)|Nina Shatskaya]] as Elena Konstantinovna Gvozdilova\n* [[Sergey Makovetskiy]] as Borya Sinyukhaev\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0100714|Sons of Bitches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sons Of Bitches}}\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:1990s drama films]]\n[[Category:Soviet films]]\n[[Category:Soviet drama films]]\n[[Category:Russian-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:1990 directorial debut films]]\n\n\n{{1990s-USSR-film-stub}}\n{{1990s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sons_of_Bitches"}
{"title_page": "1906 Tour de France", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1906 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1906 map-fr.svg\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1906 Tour de France followed clockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = Map of France with the route of the 1906 Tour de France on it, showing that the race started in Paris, went clockwise through France and ended in Paris after thirteen stages.\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 4\u201329 July\n| stages             = 13\n| distance           = 4637\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 31 points\n| first              = [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]\n| first_nat          = FRA\n| second             = [[Georges Passerieu]]\n| second_nat         = FRA\n| third              = [[Louis Trousselier]]\n| third_nat          = FRA\n| previous           = [[1905 Tour de France|1905]]\n| next               = [[1907 Tour de France|1907]]\n}}\nThe '''1906 Tour de France''' was the fourth of the edition [[Tour de France]], and second to use the point system. Taking place from 4 to 29 July the total race distance was {{convert|4637|km}} run over 13 stages, with the winner averaging {{convert|24.463|km/h}}.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}} New in this year were the mountain climbs in the [[Massif Central]]. Like its predecessors, it still had cheating and sabotage taking place. Four competitors were disqualified for taking trains as a shortcut and spectators threw nails in the road. However, this did not stop [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]] from taking a big lead in the first stages. Free of tendinitis that plagued his 1905 chances, he dominated the entire race.<ref name=\"TdF1906\">{{cite web |url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1906/histoire.html |title=1906 \u2013 4th Tour de France |publisher=ASO |accessdate=24 March 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gVck7QGQ?url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/1907/us/annee.html?RaceYear=1907&x=23&y=4 |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n==Innovations and changes==\nTour organiser [[Henri Desgrange]] had been happy with the increased length of the [[1905 Tour de France]], and decided to put even more stages in the 1906 version.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=9\u201310}}\n\nThe introduction of mountain stages had also been successful, so this year not only the [[Vosges Mountains|Vosges]] were included, but also the [[Massif Central]].<ref name=\"Velo1906\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1906.php|title=1906: The first climbing star is born|first=Tom|last=James|date=14 August 2003|accessdate=24 March 2009|publisher=VeloArchive}}</ref>\n\nThe increased length made it possible to follow the borders of France, and in 1906 the perimeter was closely followed.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=16\u201319}}\n\n{{hide in print|[[File:Flamme-Rouge-TdF2004.jpg|left|thumb|The ''flamme rouge'', indicating the final kilometre of the stage, was introduced in the 1906 Tour de France.|alt=A structure above a road, with a red triangle in the middle, with a car passing under the structure.]]}}The points system in the 1905 Tour de France had been successful enough in reducing cheating, so the Tour organisers used it again in the 1906 Tour de France, with a few changes: whereas in 1905, time differences still had some effect on the points distribution, in 1906 time differences were unimportant, and points were only given for the order in which the cyclists finished. The winner of the stage received one point, the second rider two points, et cetera. After the eighth stage, only 16 cyclists were remaining, and the results from the first eight stages were recalculated, with only the remaining cyclists, and the points were redistributed among the remaining riders in accordance with their positions in those stages.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/>\n\nThe first stage ended in Lille and the second stage started in Douai; this was the first time that a stage did not start where the previous stage ended.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/>\nAlso for the first time, the Tour went outside France: in the second stage, [[Germany]] ([[Alsace-Lorraine]] was then part of Germany)<ref name=\"TdF1906\"/> was visited, then several days later Italy ([[Ventimiglia]]) and [[Spain]] ([[Irun]]) too.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/><ref>''Le Tour de France pour les Nuls'' by Jean-Paul Vespini, First-Gr\u00fcnd, 2013, Paris.</ref>\n\nThe 1906 Tour also saw the introduction of the ''flamme rouge'' (red flame), a red flag that indicates that the cyclists only have one kilometre to go.<ref name=\"TdF1906\"/>\n\n==Participants==\n{{main list|List of cyclists in the 1906 Tour de France}}\n\nThere were 100 cyclists signed up for the race, but only 76 of them came to the start. One of the absentees was [[Henri Cornet]], winner of the [[1904 Tour de France]]. Four cyclists were Belgian, one was Luxembourgian (later winner [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]), two were German, and the rest were French.<ref name=\"mdc1906\" /> [[Louis Trousselier]], winner of the [[1905 Tour de France]], was present. The riders were not grouped in teams, but some cyclists had the same sponsor, even though they were not allowed to work together.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=36}} Before the race started, most was expected from Cadolle, Aucouturier, Georget, Pottier, Trousselier, Dortignac and Petit-Breton.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD02/HEM/1906/07/12/MD19060712-004.pdf|title=El \"Tour de France\" 1906|date=12 July 1906|language=Spanish|work=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|page=4|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006192028/http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD02/HEM/1906/07/12/MD19060712-004.pdf|archive-date=6 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs in 1905, the cyclists were divided in two categories, the ''coureurs de vitesse'' and the ''coureurs sur machines poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es'', where the riders in the first category were allowed to change bicycles, which could be an advantage in the mountains, where they could use a bicycle with lower gears. In 1905, sponsors had not been so enthusiastic about entering their cyclists in this category, but in 1906 they had learned that it had a commercial advantage to have cyclists starting in the poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es category, because the average French citizen could identify more with them. In 1906, more than half of the cyclists started in the poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es category, including Lucien Petit-Breton, one of the pre-favourites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wielrennen.miegum.nl/00000013.html |title=Gelode fietsen |accessdate=19 July 2010 |language=Dutch |work=Heersers van de Weg |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902091848/http://wielrennen.miegum.nl/00000013.html |archivedate=2 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Race overview==\n\n{{main|1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7|1906 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 13}}\n\n[[File:Hippolyte Aucouturier 1906.jpg|thumb|right|[[Hippolyte Aucouturier]] fixing a flat tire|alt=A man working on the front tire of a bicycle; three men are watching.]]\nAs in previous years, the spectators tried to assist their preferred riders by trying to impede their opponents.<ref name=\"convicts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lorrainemace.com/index_files/Page1342.html |title=Convicts of the road |first=Lorraine |last=Mace |year=2004 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gVcirhlK?url=http://www.lorrainemace.com/index_files/Page1342.html |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=dead |accessdate=19 July 2010 |publisher=Lorraine Mace.com  }}</ref> On the first stage, nails had been thrown on the road, and all cyclists except [[Lucien Petit-Breton]] punctured.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/> This stage was won by [[Emile Georget]] in a sprint.\n\nIn the second stage, [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]], who had shown his climbing abilities in the previous edition, aimed for the victory.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=16\u201319}} He was stopped after {{convert|175|km}} with mechanical failure, and he lost 58&nbsp;minutes. The other main contenders worked together to stay away from Pottier, but Pottier chased them for {{convert|200|km}}, caught them {{convert|25|km}} before the finish, and even left them behind, winning the stage with a margin of 1'30\" on Petit-Breton and more than 9 minutes on the rest.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=9\u201310}}\n\nIn the third stage, four cyclists ([[Julien Gabory]], [[Henri Gauban]], [[Gaston Tuvache]] and [[Maurice Carrere]]) were disqualified for taking the train.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/> The [[Col du Ballon d'Alsace|Ballon d'Alsace]], which had been the first real mountain in the Tour de France the previous year, was featured again. Just as the year before, it was mounted first by Pottier.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=9\u201310}} The stage was also won by Pottier, more than 45 minutes ahead of the rest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1906_3.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120223121656/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1906_3.php |archive-date=23 February 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |language=French |title=4\u00e8me Tour de France 1906 \u2013 3\u00e8me \u00e9tappe }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tour de France 1906 (01).jpg|thumb|left|The 1906 Tour passing through a town|alt=A square with two lines of crowd diagonally, with cyclist between them going to the lower right, and horses outside them.]]\nPottier also won the fourth stage. In the fifth stage, he was leading by one hour at the halfway point. A cycling legend says that he decided to stop, entered a bar and ordered a bottle of wine, and drank it almost completely. When he saw the first other cyclists passing by, Pottier mounted his bicycle again, went after them, and won the stage.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=9\u201310}} By this point, Pottier was leading the overall classification firmly. The winner of the 1905 Tour de France, [[Louis Trousselier]], had had a bad first half of the Tour, and was many points behind. Trousselier rediscovered his form in the second half of the race, won the 7th, 9th, 10th and 11th stages, and was challenging the second place of [[Georges Passerieu]]. Passerieu defended his position by winning the 12th stage.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=9\u201310}} In the last stage, Pottier showed his strength by winning the stage,{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=9\u201310}} after finishing together in Paris with Passerieu.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Results==\n[[File:Louis Trousselier.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Louis Trousselier]], winner of four stages in the 1906 Tour de France.|alt=A black-and-white photograph of a man with three-colored sweater and shorts with a moustache sitting on a bicycle.]]\n\n===Stage results===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1906\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1906.php |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=4\u00e8me Tour de France 1906 |language=French |accessdate=24 March 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gVcjgIxR?url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1906.php |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=8}}\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type{{efn|In 1906, there was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate that only the third and fifth stage included mountains.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/>}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" | Race leader\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 4 July || [[Paris]] to [[Lille]]\n| {{convert|275|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 2|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 6 July || [[Douai]] to [[Nancy, France|Nancy]]\n| {{convert|400|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 8 July || [[Nancy, France|Nancy]] to [[Dijon]]\n| {{convert|416|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 10 July || [[Dijon]] to [[Grenoble]]\n| {{convert|311|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 5|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 12 July || [[Grenoble]] to [[Nice]]\n| {{convert|345|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 6|6]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 14 July || [[Nice]] to [[Marseille]]\n| {{convert|292|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Passerieu]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16 July || [[Marseille]] to [[Toulouse]]\n| {{convert|480|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 13#Stage 8|8]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 18 July || [[Toulouse]] to [[Bayonne]]\n| {{convert|300|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 13#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 20 July || [[Bayonne]] to [[Bordeaux]]\n| {{convert|338|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 13#Stage 10|10]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 22 July || [[Bordeaux]] to [[Nantes]]\n| {{convert|391|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 13#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 24 July || [[Nantes]] to [[Brest, France|Brest]]\n| {{convert|321|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 13#Stage 12|12]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 26 July || [[Brest, France|Brest]] to [[Caen]]\n| {{convert|415|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Passerieu]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 13#Stage 13|13]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 29 July || [[Caen]] to [[Paris]]\n| {{convert|259|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|4637|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n\nAfter the 13th stage, the race was followed by two timed exhibition laps on the Velodrome in Paris, the result of which was not counted for the overall classification. The winner was [[Emile Georget]], who finished the {{convert|1332|m}} in 2:07.20.<ref name=\"Velo1906\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1906_13.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222104358/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1906_13.php |archive-date=22 February 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=4\u00e8me Tour de France 1906 \u2013 14\u00e8me \u00e9tape |language=French }}</ref>\n\n===General classification===\n[[File:Tour de France 1906 (02).jpg|thumb|right|[[Georges Passerieu]] (left) and [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]] (right), preparing for their honorary lap after the Tour ended.|alt=Two men with flowers in their hands, sitting on bicycles being held by other men, with the Eiffel tower seen in the background.]]\nOne hundred cyclists had entered for the 1906 Tour de France; only 82 of them showed up at the start. Only 49 cyclists finished the first stage, and the number of active cyclists quickly fell to 37 in stage two, 29 in stage three, until 16 after stage eight. At that point, the points given in the first eight stages were redistributed among the remaining riders in accordance with their positions in those stages. At the end of the Tour de France, only 14 cyclists finished.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/> The cyclists were not grouped in teams; some cyclists had the same sponsor, but they were not allowed to work together.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=36}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:40em; margin-bottom:0;\"\n|+ Final general classification (1\u201310)<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/>\n|-\n! width=40 | Rank\n! width=200 | Rider\n! width=150 | Sponsor\n! width=40 | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 31\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Passerieu]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 39\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 61\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Petit-Breton]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 65\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}} || [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon\u2013Dunlop]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 80\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alo\u00efs Catteau]]|BEL}} || [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon\u2013Dunlop]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 129\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 7\n| {{flagathlete|[[\u00c9douard Wattelier]]|FRA}} || Labor || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 137\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 8\n| {{flagathlete|[[L\u00e9on Georget]]|FRA}} || [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon\u2013Dunlop]] || align=right|152\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}} || Labor || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 156\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 10\n| {{flagathlete|[[Anthony Wattelier]]|FRA}} || [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon\u2013Dunlop]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 168\n|}\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed wikitable noprint\" style=\"width:40em;margin-top:-1px;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"4\" | Final general classification (11\u201314)\n|-\n! width=40 | Rank\n! width=200 | Rider\n! width=150 | Sponsor\n! width=40 | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 11\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Fleury]]|FRA}} || Rochet || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 201\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 12\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ferdinand Payan]]|FRA}} || Chapmeyrache/MIC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 222\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 13\n| {{flagathlete|[[L\u00e9on Winant]]|FRA}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 241\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 14\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Bronchard]]|FRA}} || Biguet || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 256\n|}\n\n===Other classifications===\nLucien Petit-Breton was the winner of the \"machines poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\" category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1906/histoire.html|title=l'Historique du Tour \u2013 Ann\u00e9e 1906|language=French|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=30 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716170705/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1906/histoire.html|archive-date=16 July 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe organising newspaper l'Auto named [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]] the ''meilleur grimpeur''. This unofficial title is the precursor to the [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]].{{sfn|Cleijne|2014|p=156}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe Tour organisers did not make many changes the rules or route for the next race, because they had worked in the 1906 Tour de France. The revised points system would be kept in this form until 1911, only to be changed a little bit in 1912 before being replaced by the time system in 1913. The flamme rouge that was introduced in 1906 to indicate the final kilometre of a stage was kept and is still in use.\n\nRen\u00e9 Pottier would not defend his title in the [[1907 Tour de France]], because he would commit suicide before, after discovering that his wife had had an affair while he was riding the Tour.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=16\u201319}} Petit-Breton and Georget would start again in the 1907 Tour and duel for the overall victory, which would be won by Petit-Breton.\n\nTo honor Pottier's achievements on the Ballon d'Alsace, a monument was placed for him on top of that mountain.<ref name=\"revealed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/timeline/Race%20Snippets/TdF/TdF1906.htm|title=The Thrill of Victory, the Agony of Life|last=Boyce|first=Barry|year=2004|publisher=Cyclingrevealed|accessdate=19 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last=Amels|first=Wim|title=De geschiedenis van de Tour de France 1903\u20131984|location=Valkenswaard, Netherlands|publisher=Sport-Express|year=1984|language=Dutch|isbn=978-90-70763-05-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cleijne|first=Jan|title=Legends of the Tour|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3nCNAwAAQBAJ|year=2014|location=London|publisher=Head of Zeus|isbn=978-1-78185-998-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Christopher S.|title=The Tour de France: A Cultural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M-vUF6Y_4RUC|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|location=Oakland, CA|year=2006|isbn=978-0-520-24760-4|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de France 1906|1906 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1906 Tour de France|1|7|8|13}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1906 Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1906 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1906 in French sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:1906 in road cycling|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:July 1906 sports events|Tour de France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1906 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1906 map-fr.svg\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1906 Tour de France followed clockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = Map of France with the route of the 1906 Tour de France on it, showing that the race started in Paris, went clockwise through France and ended in Paris after thirteen stages.\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 4\u201329 July\n| stages             = 13\n| distance           = 4637\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 31 points\n| first              = [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]\n| first_nat          = FRA\n| second             = [[Georges Passerieu]]\n| second_nat         = FRA\n| third              = [[Louis Trousselier]]\n| third_nat          = FRA\n| previous           = [[1905 Tour de France|1905]]\n| next               = [[1907 Tour de France|1907]]\n}}\nThe '''1906 Tour de France''' was the fourth of the edition [[Tour de France]], and second to use the point system. Taking place from 4 to 29 July the total race distance was {{convert|4637|km}} run over 13 stages, with the winner averaging {{convert|24.463|km/h}}.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}} New in this year were the mountain climbs in the [[Massif Central]]. Like its predecessors, it still had cheating and sabotage taking place. Four competitors were disqualified for taking trains as a shortcut and spectators threw nails in the road. However, this did not stop [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]] from taking a big lead in the first stages. Free of tendinitis that plagued his 1905 chances, he dominated the entire race.<ref name=\"TdF1906\">{{cite web |url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1906/histoire.html |title=1906 \u2013 4th Tour de France |publisher=ASO |accessdate=24 March 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gVck7QGQ?url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/1907/us/annee.html?RaceYear=1907&x=23&y=4 |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n==Innovations==\nTour organiser [[Henri Desgrange]] had been happy with the increased length of the [[1905 Tour de France]], and decided to put even more stages in the 1906 version.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=9\u201310}}\n\nThe introduction of mountain stages had also been successful, so this year not only the [[Vosges Mountains|Vosges]] were included, but also the [[Massif Central]].<ref name=\"Velo1906\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1906.php|title=1906: The first climbing star is born|first=Tom|last=James|date=14 August 2003|accessdate=24 March 2009|publisher=VeloArchive}}</ref>\n\nThe increased length made it possible to follow the borders of France, and in 1906 the perimeter was closely followed.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=16\u201319}}\n\n{{hide in print|[[File:Flamme-Rouge-TdF2004.jpg|left|thumb|The ''flamme rouge'', indicating the final kilometre of the stage, was introduced in the 1906 Tour de France.|alt=A structure above a road, with a red triangle in the middle, with a car passing under the structure.]]}}The points system in the 1905 Tour de France had been successful enough in reducing cheating, so the Tour organisers used it again in the 1906 Tour de France, with a few changes: whereas in 1905, time differences still had some effect on the points distribution, in 1906 time differences were unimportant, and points were only given for the order in which the cyclists finished. The winner of the stage received one point, the second rider two points, et cetera. After the eighth stage, only 16 cyclists were remaining, and the results from the first eight stages were recalculated, with only the remaining cyclists, and the points were redistributed among the remaining riders in accordance with their positions in those stages.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/>\n\nThe first stage ended in Lille and the second stage started in Douai; this was the first time that a stage did not start where the previous stage ended.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/>\nAlso for the first time, the Tour went outside France: in the second stage, [[Germany]] ([[Alsace-Lorraine]] was then part of Germany)<ref name=\"TdF1906\"/> was visited, then several days later Italy ([[Ventimiglia]]) and [[Spain]] ([[Irun]]) too.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/><ref>''Le Tour de France pour les Nuls'' by Jean-Paul Vespini, First-Gr\u00fcnd, 2013, Paris.</ref>\n\nThe 1906 Tour also saw the introduction of the ''flamme rouge'' (red flame), a red flag that indicates that the cyclists only have one kilometre to go.<ref name=\"TdF1906\"/>\n\n==Participants==\n{{main list|List of cyclists in the 1906 Tour de France}}\n\nThere were 100 cyclists signed up for the race, but only 76 of them came to the start. One of the absentees was [[Henri Cornet]], winner of the [[1904 Tour de France]]. Four cyclists were Belgian, one was Luxembourgian (later winner [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]), two were German, and the rest were French.<ref name=\"mdc1906\" /> [[Louis Trousselier]], winner of the [[1905 Tour de France]], was present. The riders were not grouped in teams, but some cyclists had the same sponsor, even though they were not allowed to work together.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=36}} Before the race started, most was expected from Cadolle, Aucouturier, Georget, Pottier, Trousselier, Dortignac and Petit-Breton.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD02/HEM/1906/07/12/MD19060712-004.pdf|title=El \"Tour de France\" 1906|date=12 July 1906|language=Spanish|work=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|page=4|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006192028/http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD02/HEM/1906/07/12/MD19060712-004.pdf|archive-date=6 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs in 1905, the cyclists were divided in two categories, the ''coureurs de vitesse'' and the ''coureurs sur machines poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es'', where the riders in the first category were allowed to change bicycles, which could be an advantage in the mountains, where they could use a bicycle with lower gears. In 1905, sponsors had not been so enthusiastic about entering their cyclists in this category, but in 1906 they had learned that it had a commercial advantage to have cyclists starting in the poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es category, because the average French citizen could identify more with them. In 1906, more than half of the cyclists started in the poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es category, including Lucien Petit-Breton, one of the pre-favourites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wielrennen.miegum.nl/00000013.html |title=Gelode fietsen |accessdate=19 July 2010 |language=Dutch |work=Heersers van de Weg |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902091848/http://wielrennen.miegum.nl/00000013.html |archivedate=2 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Race overview==\n\n{{main|1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7|1906 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 13}}\n\n[[File:Hippolyte Aucouturier 1906.jpg|thumb|right|[[Hippolyte Aucouturier]] fixing a flat tire|alt=A man working on the front tire of a bicycle; three men are watching.]]\nAs in previous years, the spectators tried to assist their preferred riders by trying to impede their opponents.<ref name=\"convicts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lorrainemace.com/index_files/Page1342.html |title=Convicts of the road |first=Lorraine |last=Mace |year=2004 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gVcirhlK?url=http://www.lorrainemace.com/index_files/Page1342.html |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=dead |accessdate=19 July 2010 |publisher=Lorraine Mace.com  }}</ref> On the first stage, nails had been thrown on the road, and all cyclists except [[Lucien Petit-Breton]] punctured.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/> This stage was won by [[Emile Georget]] in a sprint.\n\nIn the second stage, [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]], who had shown his climbing abilities in the previous edition, aimed for the victory.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=16\u201319}} He was stopped after {{convert|175|km}} with mechanical failure, and he lost 58&nbsp;minutes. The other main contenders worked together to stay away from Pottier, but Pottier chased them for {{convert|200|km}}, caught them {{convert|25|km}} before the finish, and even left them behind, winning the stage with a margin of 1'30\" on Petit-Breton and more than 9 minutes on the rest.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=9\u201310}}\n\nIn the third stage, four cyclists ([[Julien Gabory]], [[Henri Gauban]], [[Gaston Tuvache]] and [[Maurice Carrere]]) were disqualified for taking the train.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/> The [[Col du Ballon d'Alsace|Ballon d'Alsace]], which had been the first real mountain in the Tour de France the previous year, was featured again. Just as the year before, it was mounted first by Pottier.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=9\u201310}} The stage was also won by Pottier, more than 45 minutes ahead of the rest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1906_3.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120223121656/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1906_3.php |archive-date=23 February 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |language=French |title=4\u00e8me Tour de France 1906 \u2013 3\u00e8me \u00e9tappe }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tour de France 1906 (01).jpg|thumb|left|The 1906 Tour passing through a town|alt=A square with two lines of crowd diagonally, with cyclist between them going to the lower right, and horses outside them.]]\nPottier also won the fourth stage. In the fifth stage, he was leading by one hour at the halfway point. A cycling legend says that he decided to stop, entered a bar and ordered a bottle of wine, and drank it almost completely. When he saw the first other cyclists passing by, Pottier mounted his bicycle again, went after them, and won the stage.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=9\u201310}} By this point, Pottier was leading the overall classification firmly. The winner of the 1905 Tour de France, [[Louis Trousselier]], had had a bad first half of the Tour, and was many points behind. Trousselier rediscovered his form in the second half of the race, won the 7th, 9th, 10th and 11th stages, and was challenging the second place of [[Georges Passerieu]]. Passerieu defended his position by winning the 12th stage.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=9\u201310}} In the last stage, Pottier showed his strength by winning the stage,{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=9\u201310}} after finishing together in Paris with Passerieu.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Results==\n[[File:Louis Trousselier.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Louis Trousselier]], winner of four stages in the 1906 Tour de France.|alt=A black-and-white photograph of a man with three-colored sweater and shorts with a moustache sitting on a bicycle.]]\n\n===Stage results===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1906\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1906.php |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=4\u00e8me Tour de France 1906 |language=French |accessdate=24 March 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gVcjgIxR?url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1906.php |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=8}}\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type{{efn|In 1906, there was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate that only the third and fifth stage included mountains.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/>}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" | Race leader\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 4 July || [[Paris]] to [[Lille]]\n| {{convert|275|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 2|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 6 July || [[Douai]] to [[Nancy, France|Nancy]]\n| {{convert|400|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 8 July || [[Nancy, France|Nancy]] to [[Dijon]]\n| {{convert|416|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 10 July || [[Dijon]] to [[Grenoble]]\n| {{convert|311|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 5|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 12 July || [[Grenoble]] to [[Nice]]\n| {{convert|345|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 6|6]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 14 July || [[Nice]] to [[Marseille]]\n| {{convert|292|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Passerieu]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16 July || [[Marseille]] to [[Toulouse]]\n| {{convert|480|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 13#Stage 8|8]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 18 July || [[Toulouse]] to [[Bayonne]]\n| {{convert|300|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 13#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 20 July || [[Bayonne]] to [[Bordeaux]]\n| {{convert|338|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 13#Stage 10|10]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 22 July || [[Bordeaux]] to [[Nantes]]\n| {{convert|391|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 13#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 24 July || [[Nantes]] to [[Brest, France|Brest]]\n| {{convert|321|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 13#Stage 12|12]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 26 July || [[Brest, France|Brest]] to [[Caen]]\n| {{convert|415|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Passerieu]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1906 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 13#Stage 13|13]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 29 July || [[Caen]] to [[Paris]]\n| {{convert|259|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|4637|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n\nAfter the 13th stage, the race was followed by two timed exhibition laps on the Velodrome in Paris, the result of which was not counted for the overall classification. The winner was [[Emile Georget]], who finished the {{convert|1332|m}} in 2:07.20.<ref name=\"Velo1906\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1906_13.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222104358/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1906_13.php |archive-date=22 February 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=4\u00e8me Tour de France 1906 \u2013 14\u00e8me \u00e9tape |language=French }}</ref>\n\n===General classification===\n[[File:Tour de France 1906 (02).jpg|thumb|right|[[Georges Passerieu]] (left) and [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]] (right), preparing for their honorary lap after the Tour ended.|alt=Two men with flowers in their hands, sitting on bicycles being held by other men, with the Eiffel tower seen in the background.]]\nOne hundred cyclists had entered for the 1906 Tour de France; only 82 of them showed up at the start. Only 49 cyclists finished the first stage, and the number of active cyclists quickly fell to 37 in stage two, 29 in stage three, until 16 after stage eight. At that point, the points given in the first eight stages were redistributed among the remaining riders in accordance with their positions in those stages. At the end of the Tour de France, only 14 cyclists finished.<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/> The cyclists were not grouped in teams; some cyclists had the same sponsor, but they were not allowed to work together.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=36}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:40em; margin-bottom:0;\"\n|+ Final general classification (1\u201310)<ref name=\"mdc1906\"/>\n|-\n! width=40 | Rank\n! width=200 | Rider\n! width=150 | Sponsor\n! width=40 | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 31\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Passerieu]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 39\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 61\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Petit-Breton]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 65\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}} || [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon\u2013Dunlop]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 80\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alo\u00efs Catteau]]|BEL}} || [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon\u2013Dunlop]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 129\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 7\n| {{flagathlete|[[\u00c9douard Wattelier]]|FRA}} || Labor || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 137\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 8\n| {{flagathlete|[[L\u00e9on Georget]]|FRA}} || [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon\u2013Dunlop]] || align=right|152\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}} || Labor || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 156\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 10\n| {{flagathlete|[[Anthony Wattelier]]|FRA}} || [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon\u2013Dunlop]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 168\n|}\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed wikitable noprint\" style=\"width:40em;margin-top:-1px;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"4\" | Final general classification (11\u201314)\n|-\n! width=40 | Rank\n! width=200 | Rider\n! width=150 | Sponsor\n! width=40 | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 11\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Fleury]]|FRA}} || Rochet || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 201\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 12\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ferdinand Payan]]|FRA}} || Chapmeyrache/MIC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 222\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 13\n| {{flagathlete|[[L\u00e9on Winant]]|FRA}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 241\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 14\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Bronchard]]|FRA}} || Biguet || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 256\n|}\n\n===Other classifications===\nLucien Petit-Breton was the winner of the \"machines poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\" category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1906/histoire.html|title=l'Historique du Tour \u2013 Ann\u00e9e 1906|language=French|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=30 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716170705/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1906/histoire.html|archive-date=16 July 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe organising newspaper l'Auto named [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]] the ''meilleur grimpeur''. This unofficial title is the precursor to the [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]].{{sfn|Cleijne|2014|p=156}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe Tour organisers did not make many changes the rules or route for the next race, because they had worked in the 1906 Tour de France. The revised points system would be kept in this form until 1911, only to be changed a little bit in 1912 before being replaced by the time system in 1913. The flamme rouge that was introduced in 1906 to indicate the final kilometre of a stage was kept and is still in use.\n\nRen\u00e9 Pottier would not defend his title in the [[1907 Tour de France]], because he would commit suicide before, after discovering that his wife had had an affair while he was riding the Tour.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=16\u201319}} Petit-Breton and Georget would start again in the 1907 Tour and duel for the overall victory, which would be won by Petit-Breton.\n\nTo honor Pottier's achievements on the Ballon d'Alsace, a monument was placed for him on top of that mountain.<ref name=\"revealed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/timeline/Race%20Snippets/TdF/TdF1906.htm|title=The Thrill of Victory, the Agony of Life|last=Boyce|first=Barry|year=2004|publisher=Cyclingrevealed|accessdate=19 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last=Amels|first=Wim|title=De geschiedenis van de Tour de France 1903\u20131984|location=Valkenswaard, Netherlands|publisher=Sport-Express|year=1984|language=Dutch|isbn=978-90-70763-05-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cleijne|first=Jan|title=Legends of the Tour|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3nCNAwAAQBAJ|year=2014|location=London|publisher=Head of Zeus|isbn=978-1-78185-998-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Christopher S.|title=The Tour de France: A Cultural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M-vUF6Y_4RUC|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|location=Oakland, CA|year=2006|isbn=978-0-520-24760-4|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de France 1906|1906 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1906 Tour de France|1|7|8|13}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1906 Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1906 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1906 in French sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:1906 in road cycling|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:July 1906 sports events|Tour de France]]\n", "name_user": "BaldBoris", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInnovations and changes:Innovations \u2192 Innovations and changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1906_Tour_de_France"}
{"title_page": "1905 Tour de France", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1905 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1905 map-fr.svg\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1905 Tour de France followed clockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = Map of France with the route of the 1905 Tour de France on it, showing that the race started in Paris, went clockwise through France and ended in Paris after eleven stages.\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 9\u201330 July\n| stages             = 11\n| distance           = 2994\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 35 points\n| first              = [[Louis Trousselier]]\n| first_nat          = FRA\n| second             = [[Hippolyte Aucouturier]]\n| second_nat         = FRA\n| third              = [[Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq]]\n| third_nat          = FRA\n| previous           = [[1904 Tour de France|1904]]\n| next               = [[1906 Tour de France|1906]]\n}}\nThe '''1905 Tour de France''' was the third edition of the [[Tour de France]], held from 9 to 30 July, organised by the newspaper ''[[L'Auto]]''. Following the disqualifications after the [[1904 Tour de France]], there were changes in the rules, the most important one being the general classification not made by time but by points. The race saw the introduction of mountains in the Tour de France, and [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]] excelled in the first mountain, although he could not finish the race.<ref name=\"letour\">{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1905/histoire.html|title=The Tour - Year 1905|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=29 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717054319/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1905/histoire.html|archive-date=17 July 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nDue in part to some of the rule changes, the 1905 Tour de France had less cheating and sabotage than in previous years, though they were not completely eliminated. It was won by [[Louis Trousselier]], who also won four of the eleven stages.\n\n==Innovations and changes==\n\nAfter the [[1904 Tour de France]], some cyclists were disqualified, most notably the top four cyclists of the original overall classification, [[Maurice Garin]], [[Lucien Pothier]], [[C\u00e9sar Garin]] and [[Hippolyte Aucouturier]]. Maurice Garin was originally banned for two years and Pothier for life, so they were ineligible to start the 1905 Tour de France. Of these four, only Aucouturier (who had been \"warned\" and had a \"reprimand inflicted\" on him), started the 1905 Tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1904.php|title=The Tour is finished&nbsp;... |first=Tom|last=James|date=14 August 2003|accessdate=21 June 2010|publisher=VeloArchive}}</ref> They were disqualified by the [[Union V\u00e9locip\u00e9dique Fran\u00e7aise]], based on accusations of cheating when there were no race officials around. In 1904 Tour, it was difficult to observe the cyclists continuously, as significant portions of the race were run overnight, and the long stages made it difficult to have officials everywhere.\n\nBecause these disqualifications had almost put an end to the Tour de France, the 1905 event had been changed in important ways, to make the race easier to supervise:{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}}\n*The stages were shortened so that no night riding occurred.\n*The number of stages increased to 11 stages, almost double from the previous year.\n*The winner was selected on points, not time.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1905.php|title=1905: A new formula is devised|publisher=VeloArchive|date=14 August 2003|accessdate=21 June 2010}}</ref>\nThe first cyclist to cross the finish line received 1 point. Other cyclists received one point more than the cyclist who passed the line directly before him, plus an additional point for every five minutes between them, with a maximum of ten points. In this way, a cyclist could not get more than 11 points more than the cyclist that crossed the finish line just before him.<ref name=\"mdc1905\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905.php |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=3\u00e8me Tour de France 1905 |language=French |accessdate=18 March 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520040844/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905.php |archivedate=20 May 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAs an example for this point system, the result for the first seven cyclists in the first stage is in this table:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Results of stage 1<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k561845g.zoom.f5.langFR|title=Cyclisme - Le Tour de France|language=French|work=Le Petit Parisien|publisher=Gallica Biblioth\u00e8que Num\u00e9rique|date=11 July 1905|accessdate=21 June 2010|page=5}}</ref>\n! Rank || Cyclist || Time || Difference with<br/>previous finisher||Extra points || Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| Louis Trousselier || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 11h 25'    || style=\"text-align:right;\" |  \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3' || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 3'  || style=\"text-align:right;\" |   1 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| Ren\u00e9 Pottier || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 4'             || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1'  || style=\"text-align:right;\" |   1 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 3\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| Hippolyte Aucouturier || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 26'   || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 22' || style=\"text-align:right;\" |   5 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 8\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| Henri Cornet || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 26'            || style=\"text-align:right;\" |  0'  || style=\"text-align:right;\" |   1 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 9\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| Augustin Ringeval || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 40'    || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 74' || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 11 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 20\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| Emile Georget || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 40'        || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 60' || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 11 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 31\n|}\n<!--Trousselier received one point as the winner, and Dortignac and Pottier received 2 and 3 points, being second and third. The fourth finisher, Aucouturier, was 22 minutes behind number three, so he received 5 additional points, to make 8 in total. Cornet, the next finisher, was within 5 minutes of Aucouturier, so he received only one point more, 9 points. The sixth cyclist, Ringeval, was 74 minutes behind; this would mean 15 extra points. This is more than the maximum of 11 points, so Ringeval had 20 points after the first stage instead of 24. Similar with Georget: although he was 60 minutes behind (13 points), he only received 11 extra points for this.-->\n\nThe other important introduction were the mountains. One of Desgrange's staffers, Alphonse Stein\u00e8s, took Desgrange for a trip over the [[Col Bayard]] at {{convert|1246|m|ft}} and the [[Col du Ballon d'Alsace|Ballon d'Alsace]] at {{convert|1178|m|ft}}, that had an average gradient of 5.2% with 10% at some places,{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}}<ref name=\"mdc1905\"/> to convince Desgrange to use these climbs in the route. Desgrange accepted it, saying that Stein\u00e8s would take the blame if the mountains would be too hard to climb.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}}{sfn|Laget|Bouvet|2005|pp=190\u2013191} In the two previous editions, the highest point was the [[Col de la R\u00e9publique]] at {{convert|1145|m|ft}}. In 1905, Desgrange chose to overlook this, and focused instead on the introduction of the Ballon d'Alsace, because he saw that he had missed the opportunity for publicity previously.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportgeschiedenis.nl/2007/11/10/col-de-la-republique-was-eerste-berg-in-tour-de-france.aspx|title=Col de la R\u00e9publique was eerste berg in Tour de France|author=Van den Bogaart, Ronnie|language=Dutch|date=10 November 2007|accessdate=5 July 2010|publisher=Sportgeschiedenis|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226001610/http://www.sportgeschiedenis.nl/2007/11/10/col-de-la-republique-was-eerste-berg-in-tour-de-france.aspx|archive-date=26 February 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThere were two categories of riders, the ''coureurs de vitesse'' and the ''coureurs sur machines poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es''.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=7}} The riders in the first category were allowed to change bicycles, which could be an advantage in the mountains, where they could use a bicycle with lower gears.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}} The riders in the machines poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es category had to use the same bicycle in the entire race, and to verify this, their bicycles were marked.\n\n==Participants==\n{{main list|List of cyclists in the 1905 Tour de France}}\n\nBefore the race started, 78 riders had signed up for the race. Eighteen of those did not start the race, so the Tour began with 60 riders, including former winner [[Henri Cornet]] and future winners [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]] and [[Lucien Petit-Breton]].<ref name=\"mdc1905\" /> The riders were not grouped in teams, but most of them rode with an individual sponsor. Two of the cyclists\u2014[[Alois Catteau|Catteau]] and [[Julien Lootens|Lootens]]\u2014were Belgian, all other cyclists were French. Leading up to the start of the Tour, Wattelier, [[Louis Trousselier|Trousselier]], Pottier and Augereau were all considered the most likely contenders to win the event.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k256192d.zoom.f4.langFR|language=French|title=V\u00e9locipedie - Le Tour de France de 1905|work=La Croix|date=9 July 1905|accessdate=21 June 2010|publisher=Gallica Biblioth\u00e8que Num\u00e9rique|page=4}}</ref>\n\n==Race overview==\n\n{{main|1905 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 6|1905 Tour de France, Stage 7 to Stage 11}}\n\nDespite the rule changes, there were still protesters among the spectators; in the first stage all riders except [[Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq]] punctured due to 125&nbsp;kg of nails spread along the road.<ref name=\"letour\" /><ref name=\"veloarchive\" /> The first stage was won by [[Louis Trousselier]]. Trousselier was serving the army, and had requested his commander leave for the Tour de France; this was allowed for 24 hours.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=8\u20139}} After he won the first stage and led the classification, his leave was extended until the end of the Tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/coureurmemofiche.php?coureurmemoid=846&coureurid=7607|title=Memo Louis Trousselier|publisher=CyclingWebsite|accessdate=20 March 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302033615/http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/coureurmemofiche.php?coureurmemoid=846&coureurid=7607|archive-date=2 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> From 60 starting cyclists, only 15 cyclists reached the finish line within the time limit;<ref name=\"mdc1905-1\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905_1.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506185506/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905_1.php |archive-date=6 May 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=3\u00e8me Tour de France 1905 - 1\u00e8re \u00e9tape |language=French }}</ref> 15 more reached the finish after the limit and the rest took the train.<ref name=\"nieuwsdossier\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nieuwsdossier.nl/dossier/1905-07-30/Louis+Trousselier+wint+Tour+de+France+1905|title=Louis Trousselier wint Tour de France 1905|language=Dutch|publisher=NieuwsDossier|date=8 January 2008|accessdate=21 September 2009}}</ref>\nThe Tour organiser Desgrange wanted to stop the race, but was persuaded by the cyclists not to do so, and allowed all cyclists to continue with 75 points.<ref name=\"mdc1905-1\" /><ref name=\"nieuwsdossier\" />\n\n[[File:Ren\u00e9 Pottier.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]], the first cyclist to climb a mountain in the Tour de France.|alt=A black-and-white photograph of a man with a mustache.]]\nIn the second stage, the first major climb, the [[Col du Ballon d'Alsace|Ballon d'Alsace]], made its debut. Four riders were the fastest climbers: Trousselier, [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]], Cornet and Aucouturier. Of those four, Trousselier and Aucouturier were the first to be dropped, and Cornet had to drop in the final kilometers.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}} The top was therefore reached first by Ren\u00e9 Pottier, without dismounting, at an average speed of 20&nbsp;km/h.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> Cornet, who reached the top second, had to wait 20 minutes for his bicycle with higher gear, because his support car had broken down.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}}\nLater Aucouturier caught Pottier, and dropped him, and won the stage.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}} Pottier became second in the stage and led the classification.<ref name=\"letour\"/> Seven cyclists did not reach the finish in time, but they were again allowed to start the next stage.<ref name=\"mdc1905-2\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905_2.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506185737/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905_2.php |archive-date=6 May 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=3\u00e8me Tour de France 1905 - 2\u00e8me \u00e9tape |language=French }}</ref>\n\nIn the third stage, Pottier had to abandon due to tendinitis.<ref name=\"convicts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lorrainemace.com/index_files/Page1342.html |title=Convicts of the road |first=Lorraine |last=Mace |year=2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212212010/http://lorrainemace.com/index_files/Page1342.html |archivedate=12 February 2009 |url-status=dead |accessdate=18 March 2009  }}</ref> The lead was back with Trousselier, who also won the stage.\n\nIn the fourth stage, the [[Rampe de Laffrey|C\u00f4te de Laffrey]] and the [[Col Bayard]] were climbed, the second and third mountains of the Tour de France.<ref name=\"mdc1905\"/> [[Julien Maitron]] reached both tops first, but Aucouturier won the stage. Trousselier finished in second place, still leading the overall classification, although with the same number of points as Aucouturier.<ref name=\"mdc1905-4\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905_4.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506185711/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905_4.php |archive-date=6 May 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=3\u00e8me Tour de France 1905 - 4\u00e8me \u00e9tape |language=French }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Louis Trousselier.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Louis Trousselier]], the winner of the 1905 Tour de France|alt=A black-and-white photograph of a man with three-colored sweater and shorts with a mustache sitting on a bicycle.]]In the fifth stage, Trousselier won, and because Aucouturier finished in twelfth place, Trousselier had a big lead in the general classification. After the fifth stage, Aucouturier could no longer challenge Trousselier for the lead.<ref name=\"revealed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/timeline/Race%20Snippets/TdF/TdF1905.htm|title=The Restructuring|author=Boyce, Barry|year=2004|publisher=Cycling revealed|accessdate=10 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the seventh stage to Bordeaux, Trousselier punctured after only a few kilometers. The rest of the cyclists quickly sped away from him, and Trousselier had to follow them alone for 200&nbsp;km. A few kilometers before Bordeaux, Trousselier caught up with the rest, and even managed to win the sprint.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=8\u20139}} Louis Trousselier kept his lead until the end of the race, winning five stages. Trousselier was accused of bad sportsmanship: he reportedly smashed the inkstands of a control post to prevent his opponents from signing.<ref name=\"convicts\"/> Unlike the 1904 Tour de France, no stage winners, nor anyone from the top ten of the general classification, were disqualified.\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Results==\n\n===Stage results===\n\nIn the first and last stage, the cyclists were allowed to use pacers. All the 11 stages were won by only three cyclists:{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=7}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1905\"/>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=7}}\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type{{efn|In 1905, there was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate which stages included mountains.<ref name=\"mdc1905\"/>}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" | Race leader\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 6#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9 July || [[Paris]] to [[Nancy, France|Nancy]]\n| {{convert|340|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 6#Stage 2|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 11 July || [[Nancy, France|Nancy]] to [[Besan\u00e7on]]\n| {{convert|299|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Hippolyte Aucouturier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 6#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 14 July || [[Besan\u00e7on]] to [[Grenoble]]\n| {{convert|327|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 6#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16 July || [[Grenoble]] to [[Toulon]]\n| {{convert|348|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Hippolyte Aucouturier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 6#Stage 5|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 18 July || [[Toulon]] to [[N\u00eemes]]\n| {{convert|192|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 6#Stage 6|6]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 20 July || [[N\u00eemes]] to [[Toulouse]] ||{{convert|307|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 7 to Stage 11#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 22 July || [[Toulouse]] to [[Bordeaux]] ||{{convert|268|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 7 to Stage 11#Stage 8|8]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 24 July || [[Bordeaux]] to [[La Rochelle]] ||{{convert|257|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Hippolyte Aucouturier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 7 to Stage 11#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 26 July || [[La Rochelle]] to [[Rennes]] ||{{convert|263|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 7 to Stage 11#Stage 10|10]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 28 July || [[Rennes]] to [[Caen]] ||{{convert|167|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 7 to Stage 11#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 29 July || [[Caen]] to [[Paris]] ||{{convert|253|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|2994|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n\n===General classification===\nThe cyclists officially were not grouped in teams; some cyclists had the same sponsor, even though they were not allowed to work together.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=36}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:40em; margin-bottom:0;\"\n|+Final general classification (1\u201310)<ref name=\"mdc1905\"/>\n|-\n! width=40 | Rank\n! width=200 | Rider\n! width=150 | Sponsor\n! width=40 | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]]|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 35\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Hippolyte Aucouturier]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 61\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq]]|FRA}} || Saving || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 64\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 123\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Petit-Breton]]|FRA}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 155\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Augustin Ringeval]]|FRA}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 202\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 7\n| {{flagathlete|[[Paul Chauvet]]|FRA}} || Griffon || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 231\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 8\n| {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Pautrat]]|FRA}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 248\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Julien Maitron]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]]/Griffon || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 255\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 10\n| {{flagathlete|[[Julien Gabory]]|FRA}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 304\n|}\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed wikitable noprint\" style=\"width:40em;margin-top:-1px;\"\n|-\n! colspan=4 | Final general classification (11\u201324)\n|-\n! width=40 | Rank\n! width=200 | Rider\n! width=150 | Sponsor\n! width=40 | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 11\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alois Catteau]]|BEL}} || Catteau Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 355\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 12\n| {{flagathlete|[[Martin Soulie]]|FRA}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 358\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 13\n| {{flagathlete|[[L\u00e9on Leygoute]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 394\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 14\n| {{flagathlete|[[Camille Fily]]|FRA}} || Guerin Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 415\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 15\n| {{flagathlete|[[Antony Wattelier]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 441\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 16\n| {{flagathlete|[[Henri Lignon]]|FRA}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 488\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 17\n| {{flagathlete|[[Maurice Decaup]]|FRA}} || Alcyon-Dunlop || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 490\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 18\n| {{flagathlete|[[Maurice Carrere]]|FRA}} || Pirate-Michelin || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 497\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 19\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gustave Guillarme]]|FRA}} || Renault || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 509\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 20\n| {{flagathlete|[[Julien Lootens]]|BEL}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 515\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 21\n| {{flagathlete|[[Pinchau]]|FRA}} || ? || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 707\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 22\n| {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Ventresque]]|FRA}} ||  Saving || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 792\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 23\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fernand Lallement]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 797\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 24\n| {{flagathlete|[[Clovis Lacroix]]|FRA}} ||  Saving || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 870\n|}\n\n===Other classifications===\nPautrat was the winner of the ''coureurs sur machines poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es'' category, having used the same bicycle through the whole event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1905/histoire.html|title=l'Historique du Tour - Ann\u00e9e 1905|language=French|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=29 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090715151110/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1905/histoire.html|archive-date=15 July 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe organising newspaper [[L'Auto]] named [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]] the ''meilleur grimpeur''. This unofficial title is the precursor to the [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]].{{sfn|Cleijne|2014|p=156}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe tour organisers liked the effect of the points system, and it remained active until the [[1912 Tour de France]], after which it was reverted to the time system. In [[1953 Tour de France|1953]], for the 50-years anniversary of the Tour de France, the points system was reintroduced as the [[points classification in the Tour de France|points classification]], and the winner was given a [[green jersey]]. This points classification has been active ever since.\n\nThe introduction of mountains in the Tour de France had also been successful. After the introduction of the Vosges in the 1905 Tour de France, in 1906 the [[Massif Central]] were climbed, followed by the [[Pyrenees]] in 1910 and the [[Alps]] in 1911.\n\nThe winner Trousselier received 6950 [[French Franc|Francs]] for his victory. The night after he won, he drank and gambled with friends, and lost all the money.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}} In later years, Trousselier would not win a Tour de France again, but he still won eight more stages and finished on the podium in the next year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/riders/us/1371.html |title=Past results for Louis Trousselier (FRA) |publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation|ASO]] |accessdate=20 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624054106/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/riders/us/1371.html |archivedate=24 June 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nThe unofficial mountain champion of the 1905 Tour de France, Pottier, would be more successful in the next year, when he won the overall classification and five stages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/1364.html|title=Past results for Rene Pottier (FRA)|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation|ASO]]|accessdate=20 May 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090721183945/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/1364.html|archive-date=21 July 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFor [[L'Auto]], the newspaper that organised the Tour de France, the race was a success; the circulation had increased to 100,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kb.nl/dossiers/tourdefrance/tourdefrance.html |title=Tour de France |language=Dutch |publisher=Koninklijke Bibliotheek |date=8 August 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090711063454/http://www.kb.nl/dossiers/tourdefrance/tourdefrance.html |archivedate=11 July 2009 |url-status=dead |accessdate=18 March 2009  }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last=Amels|first=Wim|title=De geschiedenis van de Tour de France 1903\u20131984|location=Valkenswaard, Netherlands|publisher=Sport-Express|year=1984|language=Dutch|isbn=978-90-70763-05-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cleijne|first=Jan|title=Legends of the Tour|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3nCNAwAAQBAJ|year=2014|location=London|publisher=Head of Zeus|isbn=978-1-78185-998-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Laget|first1=Serge|last2=Bouvet|first2=Philippe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ggx7H3q29v4C|title=Cols mythiques du Tour de France|language=French|location=Paris|publisher=[[L'\u00c9quipe]]|year=2005|isbn=978-2-915535-09-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Christopher S.|title=The Tour de France: A Cultural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M-vUF6Y_4RUC|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|location=Oakland, CA|year=2006|isbn=978-0-520-24760-4|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de France 1905|1905 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1905 Tour de France|1|6|7|11}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1905 Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1905 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1905 in French sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:1905 in road cycling|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:July 1905 sports events|Tour de France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1905 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1905 map-fr.svg\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1905 Tour de France followed clockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = Map of France with the route of the 1905 Tour de France on it, showing that the race started in Paris, went clockwise through France and ended in Paris after eleven stages.\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 9\u201330 July\n| stages             = 11\n| distance           = 2994\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 35 points\n| first              = [[Louis Trousselier]]\n| first_nat          = FRA\n| second             = [[Hippolyte Aucouturier]]\n| second_nat         = FRA\n| third              = [[Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq]]\n| third_nat          = FRA\n| previous           = [[1904 Tour de France|1904]]\n| next               = [[1906 Tour de France|1906]]\n}}\nThe '''1905 Tour de France''' was the third edition of the [[Tour de France]], held from 9 to 30 July, organised by the newspaper ''[[L'Auto]]''. Following the disqualifications after the [[1904 Tour de France]], there were changes in the rules, the most important one being the general classification not made by time but by points. The race saw the introduction of mountains in the Tour de France, and [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]] excelled in the first mountain, although he could not finish the race.<ref name=\"letour\">{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1905/histoire.html|title=The Tour - Year 1905|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=29 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717054319/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1905/histoire.html|archive-date=17 July 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nDue in part to some of the rule changes, the 1905 Tour de France had less cheating and sabotage than in previous years, though they were not completely eliminated. It was won by [[Louis Trousselier]], who also won four of the eleven stages.\n\n==Innovations==\n\nAfter the [[1904 Tour de France]], some cyclists were disqualified, most notably the top four cyclists of the original overall classification, [[Maurice Garin]], [[Lucien Pothier]], [[C\u00e9sar Garin]] and [[Hippolyte Aucouturier]]. Maurice Garin was originally banned for two years and Pothier for life, so they were ineligible to start the 1905 Tour de France. Of these four, only Aucouturier (who had been \"warned\" and had a \"reprimand inflicted\" on him), started the 1905 Tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1904.php|title=The Tour is finished&nbsp;... |first=Tom|last=James|date=14 August 2003|accessdate=21 June 2010|publisher=VeloArchive}}</ref> They were disqualified by the [[Union V\u00e9locip\u00e9dique Fran\u00e7aise]], based on accusations of cheating when there were no race officials around. In 1904 Tour, it was difficult to observe the cyclists continuously, as significant portions of the race were run overnight, and the long stages made it difficult to have officials everywhere.\n\nBecause these disqualifications had almost put an end to the Tour de France, the 1905 event had been changed in important ways, to make the race easier to supervise:{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}}\n*The stages were shortened so that no night riding occurred.\n*The number of stages increased to 11 stages, almost double from the previous year.\n*The winner was selected on points, not time.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1905.php|title=1905: A new formula is devised|publisher=VeloArchive|date=14 August 2003|accessdate=21 June 2010}}</ref>\nThe first cyclist to cross the finish line received 1 point. Other cyclists received one point more than the cyclist who passed the line directly before him, plus an additional point for every five minutes between them, with a maximum of ten points. In this way, a cyclist could not get more than 11 points more than the cyclist that crossed the finish line just before him.<ref name=\"mdc1905\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905.php |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=3\u00e8me Tour de France 1905 |language=French |accessdate=18 March 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520040844/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905.php |archivedate=20 May 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAs an example for this point system, the result for the first seven cyclists in the first stage is in this table:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Results of stage 1<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k561845g.zoom.f5.langFR|title=Cyclisme - Le Tour de France|language=French|work=Le Petit Parisien|publisher=Gallica Biblioth\u00e8que Num\u00e9rique|date=11 July 1905|accessdate=21 June 2010|page=5}}</ref>\n! Rank || Cyclist || Time || Difference with<br/>previous finisher||Extra points || Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| Louis Trousselier || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 11h 25'    || style=\"text-align:right;\" |  \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3' || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 3'  || style=\"text-align:right;\" |   1 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| Ren\u00e9 Pottier || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 4'             || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1'  || style=\"text-align:right;\" |   1 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 3\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| Hippolyte Aucouturier || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 26'   || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 22' || style=\"text-align:right;\" |   5 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 8\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| Henri Cornet || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 26'            || style=\"text-align:right;\" |  0'  || style=\"text-align:right;\" |   1 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 9\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| Augustin Ringeval || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 40'    || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 74' || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 11 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 20\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| Emile Georget || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 40'        || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 60' || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 11 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 31\n|}\n<!--Trousselier received one point as the winner, and Dortignac and Pottier received 2 and 3 points, being second and third. The fourth finisher, Aucouturier, was 22 minutes behind number three, so he received 5 additional points, to make 8 in total. Cornet, the next finisher, was within 5 minutes of Aucouturier, so he received only one point more, 9 points. The sixth cyclist, Ringeval, was 74 minutes behind; this would mean 15 extra points. This is more than the maximum of 11 points, so Ringeval had 20 points after the first stage instead of 24. Similar with Georget: although he was 60 minutes behind (13 points), he only received 11 extra points for this.-->\n\nThe other important introduction were the mountains. One of Desgrange's staffers, Alphonse Stein\u00e8s, took Desgrange for a trip over the [[Col Bayard]] at {{convert|1246|m|ft}} and the [[Col du Ballon d'Alsace|Ballon d'Alsace]] at {{convert|1178|m|ft}}, that had an average gradient of 5.2% with 10% at some places,{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}}<ref name=\"mdc1905\"/> to convince Desgrange to use these climbs in the route. Desgrange accepted it, saying that Stein\u00e8s would take the blame if the mountains would be too hard to climb.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}}{sfn|Laget|Bouvet|2005|pp=190\u2013191} In the two previous editions, the highest point was the [[Col de la R\u00e9publique]] at {{convert|1145|m|ft}}. In 1905, Desgrange chose to overlook this, and focused instead on the introduction of the Ballon d'Alsace, because he saw that he had missed the opportunity for publicity previously.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportgeschiedenis.nl/2007/11/10/col-de-la-republique-was-eerste-berg-in-tour-de-france.aspx|title=Col de la R\u00e9publique was eerste berg in Tour de France|author=Van den Bogaart, Ronnie|language=Dutch|date=10 November 2007|accessdate=5 July 2010|publisher=Sportgeschiedenis|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226001610/http://www.sportgeschiedenis.nl/2007/11/10/col-de-la-republique-was-eerste-berg-in-tour-de-france.aspx|archive-date=26 February 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThere were two categories of riders, the ''coureurs de vitesse'' and the ''coureurs sur machines poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es''.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=7}} The riders in the first category were allowed to change bicycles, which could be an advantage in the mountains, where they could use a bicycle with lower gears.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}} The riders in the machines poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es category had to use the same bicycle in the entire race, and to verify this, their bicycles were marked.\n\n==Participants==\n{{main list|List of cyclists in the 1905 Tour de France}}\n\nBefore the race started, 78 riders had signed up for the race. Eighteen of those did not start the race, so the Tour began with 60 riders, including former winner [[Henri Cornet]] and future winners [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]] and [[Lucien Petit-Breton]].<ref name=\"mdc1905\" /> The riders were not grouped in teams, but most of them rode with an individual sponsor. Two of the cyclists\u2014[[Alois Catteau|Catteau]] and [[Julien Lootens|Lootens]]\u2014were Belgian, all other cyclists were French. Leading up to the start of the Tour, Wattelier, [[Louis Trousselier|Trousselier]], Pottier and Augereau were all considered the most likely contenders to win the event.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k256192d.zoom.f4.langFR|language=French|title=V\u00e9locipedie - Le Tour de France de 1905|work=La Croix|date=9 July 1905|accessdate=21 June 2010|publisher=Gallica Biblioth\u00e8que Num\u00e9rique|page=4}}</ref>\n\n==Race overview==\n\n{{main|1905 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 6|1905 Tour de France, Stage 7 to Stage 11}}\n\nDespite the rule changes, there were still protesters among the spectators; in the first stage all riders except [[Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq]] punctured due to 125&nbsp;kg of nails spread along the road.<ref name=\"letour\" /><ref name=\"veloarchive\" /> The first stage was won by [[Louis Trousselier]]. Trousselier was serving the army, and had requested his commander leave for the Tour de France; this was allowed for 24 hours.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=8\u20139}} After he won the first stage and led the classification, his leave was extended until the end of the Tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/coureurmemofiche.php?coureurmemoid=846&coureurid=7607|title=Memo Louis Trousselier|publisher=CyclingWebsite|accessdate=20 March 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302033615/http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/coureurmemofiche.php?coureurmemoid=846&coureurid=7607|archive-date=2 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> From 60 starting cyclists, only 15 cyclists reached the finish line within the time limit;<ref name=\"mdc1905-1\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905_1.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506185506/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905_1.php |archive-date=6 May 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=3\u00e8me Tour de France 1905 - 1\u00e8re \u00e9tape |language=French }}</ref> 15 more reached the finish after the limit and the rest took the train.<ref name=\"nieuwsdossier\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nieuwsdossier.nl/dossier/1905-07-30/Louis+Trousselier+wint+Tour+de+France+1905|title=Louis Trousselier wint Tour de France 1905|language=Dutch|publisher=NieuwsDossier|date=8 January 2008|accessdate=21 September 2009}}</ref>\nThe Tour organiser Desgrange wanted to stop the race, but was persuaded by the cyclists not to do so, and allowed all cyclists to continue with 75 points.<ref name=\"mdc1905-1\" /><ref name=\"nieuwsdossier\" />\n\n[[File:Ren\u00e9 Pottier.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]], the first cyclist to climb a mountain in the Tour de France.|alt=A black-and-white photograph of a man with a mustache.]]\nIn the second stage, the first major climb, the [[Col du Ballon d'Alsace|Ballon d'Alsace]], made its debut. Four riders were the fastest climbers: Trousselier, [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]], Cornet and Aucouturier. Of those four, Trousselier and Aucouturier were the first to be dropped, and Cornet had to drop in the final kilometers.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}} The top was therefore reached first by Ren\u00e9 Pottier, without dismounting, at an average speed of 20&nbsp;km/h.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> Cornet, who reached the top second, had to wait 20 minutes for his bicycle with higher gear, because his support car had broken down.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}}\nLater Aucouturier caught Pottier, and dropped him, and won the stage.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}} Pottier became second in the stage and led the classification.<ref name=\"letour\"/> Seven cyclists did not reach the finish in time, but they were again allowed to start the next stage.<ref name=\"mdc1905-2\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905_2.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506185737/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905_2.php |archive-date=6 May 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=3\u00e8me Tour de France 1905 - 2\u00e8me \u00e9tape |language=French }}</ref>\n\nIn the third stage, Pottier had to abandon due to tendinitis.<ref name=\"convicts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lorrainemace.com/index_files/Page1342.html |title=Convicts of the road |first=Lorraine |last=Mace |year=2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212212010/http://lorrainemace.com/index_files/Page1342.html |archivedate=12 February 2009 |url-status=dead |accessdate=18 March 2009  }}</ref> The lead was back with Trousselier, who also won the stage.\n\nIn the fourth stage, the [[Rampe de Laffrey|C\u00f4te de Laffrey]] and the [[Col Bayard]] were climbed, the second and third mountains of the Tour de France.<ref name=\"mdc1905\"/> [[Julien Maitron]] reached both tops first, but Aucouturier won the stage. Trousselier finished in second place, still leading the overall classification, although with the same number of points as Aucouturier.<ref name=\"mdc1905-4\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905_4.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506185711/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1905_4.php |archive-date=6 May 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=3\u00e8me Tour de France 1905 - 4\u00e8me \u00e9tape |language=French }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Louis Trousselier.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Louis Trousselier]], the winner of the 1905 Tour de France|alt=A black-and-white photograph of a man with three-colored sweater and shorts with a mustache sitting on a bicycle.]]In the fifth stage, Trousselier won, and because Aucouturier finished in twelfth place, Trousselier had a big lead in the general classification. After the fifth stage, Aucouturier could no longer challenge Trousselier for the lead.<ref name=\"revealed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/timeline/Race%20Snippets/TdF/TdF1905.htm|title=The Restructuring|author=Boyce, Barry|year=2004|publisher=Cycling revealed|accessdate=10 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the seventh stage to Bordeaux, Trousselier punctured after only a few kilometers. The rest of the cyclists quickly sped away from him, and Trousselier had to follow them alone for 200&nbsp;km. A few kilometers before Bordeaux, Trousselier caught up with the rest, and even managed to win the sprint.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=8\u20139}} Louis Trousselier kept his lead until the end of the race, winning five stages. Trousselier was accused of bad sportsmanship: he reportedly smashed the inkstands of a control post to prevent his opponents from signing.<ref name=\"convicts\"/> Unlike the 1904 Tour de France, no stage winners, nor anyone from the top ten of the general classification, were disqualified.\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Results==\n\n===Stage results===\n\nIn the first and last stage, the cyclists were allowed to use pacers. All the 11 stages were won by only three cyclists:{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=7}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1905\"/>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=7}}\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type{{efn|In 1905, there was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate which stages included mountains.<ref name=\"mdc1905\"/>}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" | Race leader\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 6#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9 July || [[Paris]] to [[Nancy, France|Nancy]]\n| {{convert|340|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 6#Stage 2|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 11 July || [[Nancy, France|Nancy]] to [[Besan\u00e7on]]\n| {{convert|299|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Hippolyte Aucouturier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 6#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 14 July || [[Besan\u00e7on]] to [[Grenoble]]\n| {{convert|327|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 6#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16 July || [[Grenoble]] to [[Toulon]]\n| {{convert|348|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Hippolyte Aucouturier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 6#Stage 5|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 18 July || [[Toulon]] to [[N\u00eemes]]\n| {{convert|192|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 6#Stage 6|6]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 20 July || [[N\u00eemes]] to [[Toulouse]] ||{{convert|307|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 7 to Stage 11#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 22 July || [[Toulouse]] to [[Bordeaux]] ||{{convert|268|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 7 to Stage 11#Stage 8|8]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 24 July || [[Bordeaux]] to [[La Rochelle]] ||{{convert|257|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Hippolyte Aucouturier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 7 to Stage 11#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 26 July || [[La Rochelle]] to [[Rennes]] ||{{convert|263|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 7 to Stage 11#Stage 10|10]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 28 July || [[Rennes]] to [[Caen]] ||{{convert|167|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1905 Tour de France, Stage 7 to Stage 11#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 29 July || [[Caen]] to [[Paris]] ||{{convert|253|km|mi|abbr=on}} ||[[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|2994|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n\n===General classification===\nThe cyclists officially were not grouped in teams; some cyclists had the same sponsor, even though they were not allowed to work together.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=36}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:40em; margin-bottom:0;\"\n|+Final general classification (1\u201310)<ref name=\"mdc1905\"/>\n|-\n! width=40 | Rank\n! width=200 | Rider\n! width=150 | Sponsor\n! width=40 | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]]|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 35\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Hippolyte Aucouturier]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 61\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq]]|FRA}} || Saving || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 64\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 123\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Petit-Breton]]|FRA}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 155\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Augustin Ringeval]]|FRA}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 202\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 7\n| {{flagathlete|[[Paul Chauvet]]|FRA}} || Griffon || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 231\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 8\n| {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Pautrat]]|FRA}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 248\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Julien Maitron]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]]/Griffon || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 255\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 10\n| {{flagathlete|[[Julien Gabory]]|FRA}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 304\n|}\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed wikitable noprint\" style=\"width:40em;margin-top:-1px;\"\n|-\n! colspan=4 | Final general classification (11\u201324)\n|-\n! width=40 | Rank\n! width=200 | Rider\n! width=150 | Sponsor\n! width=40 | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 11\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alois Catteau]]|BEL}} || Catteau Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 355\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 12\n| {{flagathlete|[[Martin Soulie]]|FRA}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 358\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 13\n| {{flagathlete|[[L\u00e9on Leygoute]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 394\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 14\n| {{flagathlete|[[Camille Fily]]|FRA}} || Guerin Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 415\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 15\n| {{flagathlete|[[Antony Wattelier]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 441\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 16\n| {{flagathlete|[[Henri Lignon]]|FRA}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 488\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 17\n| {{flagathlete|[[Maurice Decaup]]|FRA}} || Alcyon-Dunlop || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 490\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 18\n| {{flagathlete|[[Maurice Carrere]]|FRA}} || Pirate-Michelin || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 497\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 19\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gustave Guillarme]]|FRA}} || Renault || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 509\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 20\n| {{flagathlete|[[Julien Lootens]]|BEL}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 515\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 21\n| {{flagathlete|[[Pinchau]]|FRA}} || ? || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 707\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 22\n| {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Ventresque]]|FRA}} ||  Saving || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 792\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 23\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fernand Lallement]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 797\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 24\n| {{flagathlete|[[Clovis Lacroix]]|FRA}} ||  Saving || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 870\n|}\n\n===Other classifications===\nPautrat was the winner of the ''coureurs sur machines poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es'' category, having used the same bicycle through the whole event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1905/histoire.html|title=l'Historique du Tour - Ann\u00e9e 1905|language=French|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=29 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090715151110/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1905/histoire.html|archive-date=15 July 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe organising newspaper [[L'Auto]] named [[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]] the ''meilleur grimpeur''. This unofficial title is the precursor to the [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]].{{sfn|Cleijne|2014|p=156}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe tour organisers liked the effect of the points system, and it remained active until the [[1912 Tour de France]], after which it was reverted to the time system. In [[1953 Tour de France|1953]], for the 50-years anniversary of the Tour de France, the points system was reintroduced as the [[points classification in the Tour de France|points classification]], and the winner was given a [[green jersey]]. This points classification has been active ever since.\n\nThe introduction of mountains in the Tour de France had also been successful. After the introduction of the Vosges in the 1905 Tour de France, in 1906 the [[Massif Central]] were climbed, followed by the [[Pyrenees]] in 1910 and the [[Alps]] in 1911.\n\nThe winner Trousselier received 6950 [[French Franc|Francs]] for his victory. The night after he won, he drank and gambled with friends, and lost all the money.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=14\u201316}} In later years, Trousselier would not win a Tour de France again, but he still won eight more stages and finished on the podium in the next year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/riders/us/1371.html |title=Past results for Louis Trousselier (FRA) |publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation|ASO]] |accessdate=20 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624054106/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/riders/us/1371.html |archivedate=24 June 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nThe unofficial mountain champion of the 1905 Tour de France, Pottier, would be more successful in the next year, when he won the overall classification and five stages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/1364.html|title=Past results for Rene Pottier (FRA)|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation|ASO]]|accessdate=20 May 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090721183945/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/1364.html|archive-date=21 July 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFor [[L'Auto]], the newspaper that organised the Tour de France, the race was a success; the circulation had increased to 100,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kb.nl/dossiers/tourdefrance/tourdefrance.html |title=Tour de France |language=Dutch |publisher=Koninklijke Bibliotheek |date=8 August 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090711063454/http://www.kb.nl/dossiers/tourdefrance/tourdefrance.html |archivedate=11 July 2009 |url-status=dead |accessdate=18 March 2009  }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last=Amels|first=Wim|title=De geschiedenis van de Tour de France 1903\u20131984|location=Valkenswaard, Netherlands|publisher=Sport-Express|year=1984|language=Dutch|isbn=978-90-70763-05-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cleijne|first=Jan|title=Legends of the Tour|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3nCNAwAAQBAJ|year=2014|location=London|publisher=Head of Zeus|isbn=978-1-78185-998-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Laget|first1=Serge|last2=Bouvet|first2=Philippe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ggx7H3q29v4C|title=Cols mythiques du Tour de France|language=French|location=Paris|publisher=[[L'\u00c9quipe]]|year=2005|isbn=978-2-915535-09-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Christopher S.|title=The Tour de France: A Cultural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M-vUF6Y_4RUC|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|location=Oakland, CA|year=2006|isbn=978-0-520-24760-4|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de France 1905|1905 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1905 Tour de France|1|6|7|11}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1905 Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1905 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1905 in French sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:1905 in road cycling|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:July 1905 sports events|Tour de France]]\n", "name_user": "BaldBoris", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInnovations and changes:Innovations \u2192 Innovations and changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1905_Tour_de_France"}
{"title_page": "Motherwell F.C. in European football", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{infobox continental football\n| continent        = Europe\n| title            = Motherwell in European football\n| image            = \n| club             = [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]]\n| caption          = \n| first entry      = [[1991\u201392 European Cup Winners' Cup]]<ref name=\"RSSSF_Fairs_Cup\"/>\n| last entry       = [[2014\u201315 UEFA Europa League]]<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2014/clubs/club=53035/profile/index.html Motherwell FC], ''[[UEFA|uefa.com]]''. Retrieved 8 August 2013.</ref>\n| european cup     = 0 (Best: Third Qualifying round)\n| uefa cup         = 0 (Best: Play-off round)\n| cup winners' cup = 0 (Best: First round)\n| intertoto cup    = \n| uefa super cup   = \n}}\n[[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell Football Club]] is a [[football in Scotland|Scottish football]] club based in the town of [[Motherwell]], [[North Lanarkshire]]. The club first competed in a European competition in [[1991\u201392 European Cup Winners' Cup|1991\u201392]], qualifying for the [[European Cup Winners' Cup]] as winners of the [[1991 Scottish Cup Final|1991 Scottish Cup]].<ref name=\"RSSSF_Fairs_Cup\">[http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec199192.html#cwc 1991-92], ''[[RSSSF|rsssf.com]]''. 17 January 2008. Retrieved 5 September 2012.</ref> The club have reached the play-off round of the [[Europa League]] twice (2010<ref name=\"10-11\">[http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2011/clubs/club=53035/matches/index.html 2010/11 Europa League], ''[[UEFA|uefa.com]]''. 13 August 2011. Retrieved 5 September 2012.</ref> and 2012<ref name=\"12-13\">[http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2013/clubs/club=53035/matches/index.html 2012/13 Europa League], ''[[UEFA|uefa.com]]''. 31 August 2012. Retrieved 5 September 2012.</ref>), which remains the club's joint best run in a European competition.\n\n==History==\n===1990s===\nMotherwell qualified for a UEFA competition for the first time in 1991\u201392 after winning the [[Scottish Cup]] the previous season. Their opponents were [[GKS Katowice]] from [[Poland]]. They won the home leg 3\u20131, but lost the away tie 2\u20130, resulting in elimination on away goals.<ref name=\"RSSSF_Fairs_Cup\"/>\n\nMotherwell qualified for the UEFA Cup for the first time in 1994\u201395 having finished third in the [[1993\u201394 Scottish Premier Division]] the previous season. They faced [[HB Torshavn]] of the [[Faroe Islands]] in the preliminary round, and advanced to the next round winning by an aggregate score of 7-1 after a 3\u20130 home leg win.<ref name=\"94-95\">[http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=1994/clubs/club=53035/matches/index.html 1994/95 UEFA Cup], ''[[UEFA|uefa.com]]''. 12 August 2011. Retrieved 5 September 2012.</ref> In the first round proper, they faced [[Germany|German]] giants [[Borussia Dortmund]]. They lost the first leg away 1-0 and lost the home second leg 2\u20130, losing 3\u20130 on aggregate.<ref name=\"94-95\"/> Motherwell finished second behind [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in the [[1994\u201395 Scottish Premier Division]], leading to qualification for the preliminary round of the [[UEFA Cup]]. They faced [[MYPA]] of [[Finland]], but lost the first leg 3\u20131 at home. A 2\u20130 away win was not enough for Motherwell to advance and they were eliminated on the [[away goals rule]].<ref name=\"95-96\">[http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=1995/clubs/club=53035/matches/index.html 1995/96 UEFA Cup], ''[[UEFA|uefa.com]]''. 12 August 2011. Retrieved 5 September 2012.</ref>\n\n===2008&ndash;15===\nAfter a 13-year absence, Motherwell returned to European football by finishing third in the [[2007-08 Scottish Premier League]]. They were drawn to face [[AS Nancy|Nancy]] of [[France]] in the first round proper. After losing the first leg 1\u20130 at the [[Stade Marcel Picot]], they then lost the second leg 2\u20130 at home, losing 3\u20130 on aggregate.<ref name=\"08-09\">[http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2009/clubs/club=53035/matches/index.html 2008/09 UEFA Cup], ''[[UEFA|uefa.com]]''. 13 August 2011. Retrieved 5 September 2012.</ref> Motherwell qualified for Europe for a second straight season after winning a place through the [[UEFA Respect Fair Play ranking|Fair Play League]], despite finishing 7th the previous season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/8039270.stm|title=Scots win Fair Play European spot|work=BBC Sport|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]]|date=8 May 2009|accessdate=September 2012}}</ref> They were the first ever Scottish entrant to the newly formed Europa League. Also, due to extensive remedial work on their [[Fir Park]] surface, Motherwell played all of their home European matches at [[Excelsior Stadium]] in [[Airdrie, North Lanarkshire|Airdrie]]. They were drawn to face [[Welsh Premier League]] side [[Llanelli A.F.C.|Llanelli]] in the first qualifying round. They suffered a shock 1\u20130 home first leg defeat, but recovered to win the away leg 3\u20130 at the [[Parc y Scarlets]].<ref name=\"09-10\">[http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2010/clubs/club=53035/matches/index.html 2009/10 Europa League], ''[[UEFA|uefa.com]]''. 13 August 2011. Retrieved 5 September 2012.</ref> In the next round they met [[KS Flamurtari Vlor\u00eb|Flamurtari]] of [[Albania]], but lost the first leg 1\u20130 away. Just like in the previous round, they recovered by hammering the Albanians 8\u20131 at home in the second, a score that stands as a record club European victory to this day.<ref name=\"09-10\"/> They advanced to the third qualifying round for a meeting with [[Romania]]n heavyweights [[FC Steaua Bucure\u0219ti|Steaua Bucure\u0219ti]]. They lost the first leg 3\u20130 away at the [[Stadionul Steaua (1974)|Stadionul Steaua]], and the second leg 3\u20131 at home. and were eliminated 6\u20131 on aggregate.<ref name=\"09-10\"/>\n\nA fifth-place finish in the [[2010-11 Scottish Premier League]] saw Motherwell qualify for Europe for a third straight season. They were to play only [[Scandinavia]]n opponents during that season's run. They first played [[Iceland]]ic club [[Brei\u00f0ablik UBK|Brei\u00f0ablik]] in the second qualifying round, winning both legs 1\u20130 to advance to the third qualifying round.<ref name=\"10-11\"/> They would then be paired with [[Aalesunds FK|Aalesunds]] of [[Norway]], and drew the first leg away 1-1, their only draw in European football, before winning the second leg 3\u20130 at [[Fir Park]].<ref name=\"10-11\"/> They were in the Europa League play-offs, the furthest they have gone in European competition, and would play [[Denmark|Danish]] outfit [[Odense Boldklub|Odense]]. They lost the first leg away 2\u20131, and lost the home second leg 1\u20130 to  bow out of Europe for another season.<ref name=\"10-11\"/>\n\nMotherwell qualified for the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] for the first time in 2012, being placed in the third qualifying round. They took the place of [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] who were in [[Administration (British football)|administration]] and were not allowed to participate. Motherwell were in the non-champions section of the draw, and were paired with [[Greece|Greek]] giants [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]]. They lost the first leg 2\u20130 at Fir Park, and went on to lose the second leg 3\u20130 at the [[Olympic Stadium (Athens)|Olympic Stadium]] in [[Athens]].<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2013/clubs/club=53035/matches/index.html 2012/13 UEFA Champions League], ''[[UEFA|uefa.com]]''. 31 August 2012. Retrieved 5 September 2012.</ref> Motherwell's elimination from the Champions League saw them parachuted into the Europa League play-off round, where they would face [[Levante UD|Levante]] of [[Spain]]. After losing the home leg 2\u20130, they then lost the second leg 1\u20130 away in [[Valencia]] to bow out of Europe 3\u20130 on aggregate and without scoring a single goal overall.<ref name=\"12-13\"/> They did, however, equal their longest participation in European competition.\n\nMotherwell finished the [[2012-13 Scottish Premier League]] in second place, and with champions [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] winning the [[2012-13 Scottish Cup]], Motherwell moved into the third qualifying round of the Europa League. They were un-seeded in that draw and were paired with [[FC Kuban Krasnodar|Kuban Krasnodar]] of [[Russia]]. They lost the first-leg 2\u20130 at Fir Park, suffering a 1\u20130 defeat in the return leg to exit European competition.<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2014/clubs/club=53035/matches/index.html 2013/14 UEFA Europa League], ''[[UEFA|uefa.com]]''. 8 August 2013. Retrieved 8 August 2013.</ref> Motherwell finished the [[2013-14 Scottish Premiership]] in second place, meaning Motherwell began in the second qualifying round of the Europa League. They were seeded in that draw and were paired with [[Stjarnan]] of [[Iceland]]. They drew the first-leg 2\u20132 at Fir Park, suffering a 3-2 extra-time defeat in the return leg to suffer elimination from that season's competition.<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2015/clubs/club=53035/matches/index.html 2014/15 UEFA Europa League], ''[[UEFA|uefa.com]]''. 22 September 2014. Retrieved 22 September 2014.</ref>\n\n==Overall record==\n===Matches===\n{|class=\"sortable plainrowheaders wikitable\" width=\"65%\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" colspan=17 | List of Motherwell games in European competitions\n|-\n! Season\n! Competition\n! Round\n! Opponent\n! Home\n! Away\n! Other\n! [[Two-legged tie|Agg.]]\n! scope=\"col\" width=15|{{efn|Round or group progressed ([[File:Symbol keep vote.svg|17px]]) or eliminated ([[File:Symbol delete vote.svg|17px]])}}\n!class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n!class=\"unsortable\"| Ref\n|-\n|[[1991\u201392 Motherwell F.C. season