,584 (100%)\n|$594,792<ref>{{cite journal|title=AB Top 10 Concert Gross|date=2000-12-16|accessdate=2010-09-15|journal=Billboard Magazine|volume=112|issue=51|page=22|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OxEEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA7&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|TOTAL\n!1,075,704 / 1,111,898 (97%)\n!$57,209,202\n|}\n\n==Critical reception==\nJosh L. Dickey (''[[Spartanburg Herald Journal]]'') praised the tour, stating, \"'In fact, the only low points came during Turner's protracted absences for outfit changes, when the backing crew was forced to carry the show. Minus Turner's soaring vocals&mdash;which cut sharply though the Target Center's infamously muddy acoustic chamber&mdash;the band seemed awkward and cursory.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tina Turner turns back the clock in tour's opener|first=Josh L.|last=Dickey|newspaper=Spartanburg Herald Journal|agency=Associated News|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=50MfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6M8EAAAAIBAJ&dq=tina%20turner%20twenty%20four%20seven%20tour&pg=4329%2C11140540|page=D6}}</ref>\n\nMark Brown (''[[Rocky Mountain News]]'') gave the performance at the Pepsi Center an \"A\", citing \"From minute one, Turner bursts onto the stage with energy and finesse that only the Queen will process. Belting out her memorable hits, Turner proves it doesn't take media trickery to have success. She may be rolling down the river but Turner is creating an untouchable path. \"<ref>{{cite news|title=Turner, Richie pull no punches in KO performances|date=2000-05-18|last=Brown|first=Mark|publisher=Denver Newspaper Agency}}</ref>\n\nMartine Bury (''[[Vibe (magazine)|VIBE]]'') praised Turner's performance at the Allstate Arena, \"From her signature rendition of Creedence Clearwater Revival's 'Proud Mary' to the way she heats up dance floors with her most recent single, 'When the Heartache is Over' that sultry, gravelly voice tells ardent stories like no other.\"<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Vibe Magazine|date=June\u2013July 2000|accessdate=2010-09-10|title=Electric Ladyland|last=Bury|first=Martine|volume=8|issue=5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SSgEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA98&dq=tina%20turner%20twenty%20four%20seven%20tour&pg=PA98#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=Vibe Media Group|page=98}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcasts and recordings==\n{{main|One Last Time Live in Concert}}\nThe opening night of the tour at the Target Center in Minneapolis, Minnesota, aired live on [[VH1]]'s Opening Night Live on March 23, 2000. The concert at the Sopot Hippodrom aired on [[TVP1]] on August 15, 2000. An additional television broadcast aired on [[BBC Three]]. The concert footage was filmed at the [[Oakland Arena]] performance on May 8, 2000. The performances filmed at the Wembley Stadium were later used for the DVD release in 2001 and aired on the CBS Network in the US. The DVD was certified platinum in the US and UK. The concert at Groningen was filmed and broadcast locally. (Footage is available on YouTube and other websites.)\n\n==Personnel==\n*Production Manager: Jake Berry\n*Lighting Designer: Roy Benney\n*Video Director: Christina Strand\n*FOH Sound Engineer: Dave Natale\n*Lighting Director: Jeff Pavey\n\n;Band\n*Drums: Jack Bruno\n*Piano: Joel Campbell\n*Supporting vocals: Joel Campbell, Ollie Marland, John Miles, James Ralston\n*Keyboards: [[Euge Groove]] and Ollie Marland\n*Saxophone and Percussions: Euge Groove\n*Bass guitar: Warren McRae\n*Guitar: [[John Miles (musician)|John Miles]] and James Ralston\n*Harmonica: John Miles\n*Backing vocals: Stacey Campbell, Solange Guenier, [[Lisa Fischer]] <small>(EU/NA-II)</small>, [[Gloria Reuben]] <small>(NA-I)</small> and Claire Louise Turton\n*Dancers: Stacey Campbell, Solange Guenier, Lisa Fischer <small>(EU/NA-II)</small>, Gloria Reuben <small>(NA-I)</small> and Claire Louise Turton, Ivona Brneli\u0107\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tinaturnerfanclub.eu/tours/twenty_four_seven_tour.html Twenty Four Seven 2000]\n*[http://www.stufish.com/tina-turner/24-seven/reality.html Stage Design]\n\n{{Tina Turner}}\n\n[[Category:Tina Turner concert tours]]\n[[Category:2000 concert tours]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox concert\n| concert_tour_name = Twenty Four Seven Tour\n\n| image             = Tfsttina.jpg\n| image_size        = 196\n| landscape         = no\n| alt               = \n| image_caption     = Promotional poster for Turner's 2000 tour\n| artist            = [[Tina Turner]]\n| location          = \n| type              = \n| album             = ''[[Twenty Four Seven (Tina Turner album)|Twenty Four Seven]]''\n| start_date        = {{Start date|2000|03|23}}\n| end_date          = {{End date|2000|12|06}}\n| number_of_legs    = 3\n| number_of_shows   = 95 in North America<br>26 in Europe<br>'''121''' Total\n|attendance = 2.6 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://991.com/Buy/ProductInformation.aspx?StockNumber=508502|title=over 2,500,000 spectators.Tours|date=|accessdate=2018-03-10|last=|first=}}</ref>\n| gross             = $122.5 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|122.5|r=2|2000}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars){{inflation-fn|US}}\n| URL               = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| last_tour         = [[Wildest Dreams Tour]]<br>(1996-97)\n| this_tour         = '''Twenty Four Seven Tour'''<br>(2000)\n| next_tour         = [[Tina!: 50th Anniversary Tour]]<br>(2008-09)\n}}\n\n'''Twenty Four Seven Tour'''  (also known as the '''Twenty Four Seven Millennium Tour''' and '''24/7 World Tour''') is the eighth concert tour by American singer, [[Tina Turner]]. The tour promoted her final studio album [[Twenty Four Seven (Tina Turner album)|''Twenty Four Seven'']]. Although she stated this numerous times in the past, Turner announced that feat would be her final \"show stopping\" tour. She stated she would continue to make records and perform at small venues and award shows. The tour was sponsored by [[E-Trade|E*Trade]].<ref name=\"nadates\">{{cite web|url=http://www.livedaily.com/news/577.html|title=First Dates Confirmed For Tina Turner's Final Tour|date=2000-02-02|accessdate=2010-09-10|last=Evans|first=Rob|work=LiveDaily|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211125745/http://livedaily.com/news/577.html|archivedate=2010-02-11}}</ref>\n\nDuring her farewell tour in 2000, Turner broke all records: never had an artist lured so much public; she played 11 times in a sold out [[Flanders Expo]] in [[Ghent]] (good for 140,000 people). During her comeback tour Turner played four times in the [[Sportpaleis]] in [[Antwerp]]. All tickets were sold out within the hour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://superleuk.be/show/simply-the-best-tribute-to-tina-turner-the-greatest-hits-tour/|title=The Queen of Rock sold out|date=February 2, 2000|accessdate=May 9, 2018|last=|first=|work=by superleuk}}</ref>\nActress [[Gloria Reuben]] served as a background dancer and singer during the first North American leg of the tour.<ref>{{cite news|title=ER nurse is semi-Private Dancer|newspaper=Toronto Sun|date=2000-05-10|page=D2}}</ref>\nAccording to [[Pollstar]], the 2000 tour became the highest-grossing tour in North America. This status was achieved over her peers, [[Barbra Streisand]] and [[Bruce Springsteen]] as well as, newcomers [['N Sync]] and [[Britney Spears]]. The North American tour dates grossed over $80 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1435473/20001228/tina_turner.jhtml|title=Tina Turner, 'NSYNC Had Year's Top-Grossing Tours|date=2000-12-28|accessdate=2010-09-10|last=Hiatt|first=Brian|work=MTV News}}</ref>\n\nWith 23 international dates included, the tour was estimated to gross more than $100 million in tickets sold. Over the course of nine months, more than two million fans came to see the soulful rock diva perform live in concert.<ref>http://www.onlinetickets.com/info/Rock-and-Pop-Tickets/Tina-Turner-24-7-Tour</ref>\n\nThe 61-year-old Turner's international \"farewell\" tour grossed a whopping $108.8 million from 89 shows by [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']].<ref>https://variety.com/2000/music/news/touring-tina-anything-but-a-private-dancer-1117791080/</ref>\n\nIt is estimated that tour grossed over 120 million dollars from 108 shows with an attendance of over 2,400,000 spectators.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=_AwEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=tina+turner+tours+attendance#v=onepage&q=tina%20turner%20tours%20attendance&f=false |title = Billboard|date = 2002-09-14}}</ref>\n\nThe concerts received additional accolades, receiving an \"Road Warrior of the Year Award\" from [[Pollstar|Pollstar Awards]].<ref>\nhttps://www.pollstarpro.com/PCIA-Static/awards2000.htm</ref>\n\nTurner would return to touring in 2008 with her [[Tina!: 50th Anniversary Tour|anniversary tour]].\n\n==Background==\nAfter her recording breaking [[Wildest Dreams Tour|1996 world tour]], Turner decided to take a longer break between albums and tours. Initially, Turner planned an elaborate co-headlining tour with [[Elton John]]. The two performed a duet of Turner's hit \"Proud Mary\" and John's \"[[The Bitch is Back]]\" on the VH1 special, \"[[Divas Live '99]]\". During rehearsals, Turner felt unease with the music and stopped everyone from playing and then instructed John on how to play the song.\n\n{{quote|text=\"I made a mistake when I needed to show him how to play 'Proud Mary'. The mistake is you don't show Elton John how to play his piano. He just went into a rage, which he apologized for later. He said it was wrong.\"|sign=Tina Turner|source=CBS News<ref name=\"CBS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2000/09/11/60minutes/main232429.shtml|title=Tina Turner Bids Farewell|date=2000-09-21|accessdate=2010-09-10|last=Wallace|first=Mike|work=CBS News|publisher=CBS Interactive Inc.}}</ref>}}\n\nThe tour plans were cancelled and Turner scrapped her initial plans for a greatest hits collection deciding to record her final studio album. Along the way, Turner also performed the [[Super Bowl XXXIV]] pre-show ceremonies.\n\nTo introduce the tour, Turner stated:<ref name=\"CBS\"/> <blockquote>It's a play. It's an act. For the moment, it's a small movie, so to speak. That's why I like all of the stuff and the action and the playoff between me and the girls. It's life on that stage for that two hours.</blockquote>\n\n==Development==\nAs mentioned above, the tour initially was set to promote her latest studio album. During promotion, Turner acknowledge the tour as her final one as she enters pseudo-retirement. She comments:<ref name=\"nadates2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.livedaily.com/news/1404.html|title=Tina Turner Mapes Second North American Leg|date=2000-07-06|accessdate=2010-09-10|last=Evans|first=Rob|work=LiveDaily|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211125545/http://livedaily.com/news/1404.html|archivedate=2010-02-11}}</ref> \n<blockquote>I've been performing for 44 years; I really should hang up my dancing shoes. I can't keep up with Janet Jackson. I'm not a diva like Diana Ross. I'm rock 'n' roll, but I'm happy I can do it one more time, so people can remember me at my best.\"</blockquote>\n\nThe album played a prominent role in the tour as Turner rehearsed \"Whatever You Need\", \"When the Heartache is Over\", \"Talk to My Heart\", \"Falling\", \"Don't Leave Me This Way\" (which was to be included in a ballads medley with \"[[Two People (song)|Two People]]\" and two other unknown songs) and \"Twenty Four Seven\". When Turner decided to do a retrospective of her career, she included her first hit, \"[[A Fool in Love]]\", the first time Turner performed the song live since the 1970s. Turner also rehearsed \"Ooh Poo Pah Do\" but replaced with \"Get Back\". Additionally, she included some of her have favorite R&B hits including, \"Hold On, I'm A Comin'\" and \"I Heard It Through the Grapevine\".\n\n{{quote|text=\"It has been described as a stadium tour in an arena. [it's] hugely complicated and one of the largest arena shows to ever go out and tour back-to-back.\"|sign=Mark Fisher}}\n\nFor her final outing, Turner wanted a stage that was sleek and modern. Her original concepts included the framing of an \"apartment building\" that had cabins and access ramps. Also included were risers with visible staircases and front drop for the musicians. Fisher, also wanted to create a volcano effect with the staging, have it split into two sets. This inner stage included a video screen and a ramp leading to an upstage platform. There was an additional ramp that lead downstage. The main feature of the stage was the \"cantilever arm\". A 2' wide, 60' long platform that extended Turner into the audience. Initially, Turner did not want the arm as the same concept was used for her [[Foreign Affair: The Farewell Tour|1990 European tour]] and she did not want to repeat herself. However, after seeing video animations, Turner wanted the arm included. For stadium shows, a roof for the stage was added along with additional video screens. The arm was extended an additional 20 feet. It took at least seven hours to construct the stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://livedesignonline.com/mag/show_business_preaching_converted_tina/|title=Preaching to the Converted: Tina Turner Roars Back on Tour|date=2000-07-01|accessdate=2010-09-10|last=Lampert-Greaux|first=Elllen|work=Live Design|publisher=Penton Media, Inc.}}</ref>\n\nThe stage was constructed by McLaren Engineering Group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgmclaren.com/node/295|title=Tina Turner 24-7 World Tour Stage|date=|accessdate=2010-09-10|last=|first=|work=McLaren Engineering Group|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Opening act==\n*[[Lionel Richie]] <small>(North America [Leg 1] & UK)</small><ref name=\"nadates1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyrock.com/worldbeat/03_2000/032300.asp|title=Lionel Richie Joins Tina Turner Tour|date=2000-03-23|accessdate=2010-09-10|work=NY Rocks|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101218212530/http://nyrock.com/worldbeat/03_2000/032300.asp|archivedate=2010-12-18}}</ref>\n*[[John Fogerty]] <small>(Europe [select dates])</small>. \n*[[Janice Robinson]] <small>(North America [Leg 1])</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20000512&slug=4020414|title=At 60, Tina Turner is still going strong on her last arena tour|date=2000-05-12|accessdate=2010-09-10|last=MacDonald|first=Patrick|work=The Seattle Times|publisher=The Seattle Times Company}}</ref>\n*[[Joe Cocker]] <small>(Europe [select dates] & North America [Leg 2])</small>\n\n==Set list==\n{{hidden\n| headercss = background: #ccccff; font-size: 100%; width: 65%;\n| contentcss = text-align: left; font-size: 100%; width: 75%;\n| header = North America (Leg I)\n| content =\n#\"Work Like you Don't Need the Money\" <small>(Instrumental Introduction)</small>\n#\"[[I Want to Take You Higher]]\"\n#\"Absolutely Nothing's Changed\"\n#\"[[A Fool in Love]]\"\n#\"[[Acid Queen]]\"\n#\"[[River Deep \u2013 Mountain High]]\"\n#\"[[We Don't Need Another Hero|We Don't Need Another Hero (Thunderdome)]]\"\n#\"[[Get Back]]\"\n#\"[[I Heard It Through the Grapevine]]\"\n#\"[[Private Dancer (Tina Turner song)|Private Dancer]]\"\n#\"[[Let's Stay Together (Al Green song)|Let's Stay Together]]\"\n#\"[[What's Love Got to Do with It (song)|What's Love Got to Do with It]]\"\n#\"[[When the Heartache Is Over]]\"\n#\"[[Baby I'm a Star]]\" <small>(performed by backing vocalist)</small>\n#\"[[Help! (song)|Help!]]\"\n#\"[[Whatever You Need (Tina Turner song)|Whatever You Need]]\"\n#\"[[Try a Little Tenderness]]\" <small>(performed with John Miles)</small>\n#\"[[Hold On, I'm A Comin']] (Performed only for the first few dates at the beginning of the tour. Shortly after replaced with \"Addicted to Love\")\"</li>\n#<li value=\"18\">\"[[Addicted To Love (song)|Addicted to Love]] (Replaced \"Hold On, I'm Comin'\" later in the tour.)\"\n#\"[[The Best (song)|The Best]]\"\n#\"[[Proud Mary]]\"\n''Encore''\n#<li value=\"21\">\"[[Nutbush City Limits]]\"</li>\n#\"Twenty Four Seven\"\n\n{{hidden\n| headercss = background: #ccccff; font-size: 100%; width: 65%;\n| contentcss = text-align: left; font-size: 100%; width: 75%;\n| header = Europe\n| content =\n#\"Work Like you Don't Need the Money\" <small>(Instrumental Introduction)</small>\n#\"I Want to Take You Higher\"\n#\"Absolutely Nothing's Changed\"\n#\"A Fool in Love\"\n#\"Acid Queen\"\n#\"River Deep \u2013 Mountain High\"\n#\"We Don't Need Another Hero (Thunderdome)\"\n#\"[[Better Be Good to Me]]\"\n#\"Private Dancer\"\n#\"Let's Stay Together\"\n#\"What's Love Got to Do with It\"\n#\"When the Heartache Is Over\"\n#\"Baby I'm a Star\" <small>(performed by backing vocalist)</small>\n#\"Help!\"\n#\"Whatever You Need\"\n#\"[[(Sittin' On) The Dock of the Bay]]\"\n#\"Try a Little Tenderness\" <small>(performed with John Miles)</small>\n#\"I Heard It Through the Grapevine\"\n#\"[[Addicted to Love (song)|Addicted To Love]]\"\n#\"The Best\"\n#\"Proud Mary\"\n''Encore''\n#<li value=\"22\">\"Nutbush City Limits\"</li>\n#<li value=\"23\">\"Twenty Four Seven\"<sup>1</sup></li>\n\n<sup>1</sup>Performed at select dates\n}}\n{{hidden\n| headercss = background: #ccccff; font-size: 100%; width: 65%;\n| contentcss = text-align: left; font-size: 100%; width: 75%;\n| header = North America (Leg II)\n| content =\n#\"Work Like you Don't Need the Money\" <small>(Instrumental Introduction)</small>\n#\"I Want to Take You Higher\"\n#\"Absolutely Nothing's Changed\"\n#\"A Fool in Love\"\n#\"Acid Queen\"\n#\"River Deep \u2013 Mountain High\"\n#\"We Don't Need Another Hero (Thunderdome)\"\n#\"Better Be Good to Me\"\n#\"Private Dancer\"\n#\"Let's Stay Together\"\n#\"What's Love Got to Do with It\"\n#\"When the Heartache Is Over\"\n#\"[[Hot Legs]]\" <small>(performed by backing vocalist)</small>\n#\"Help!\"\n#\"Whatever You Need\"\n#\"[[(Sittin' On) The Dock of the Bay]]\"\n#\"Try a Little Tenderness\" <small>(performed with John Miles)</small>\n#\"[[Steamy Windows]]\"\n#\"[[Addicted to Love (song)|Addicted To Love